Well, thanks, everybody, for
showing up live, showing up

00:00:06.540 --> 00:00:08.790
on the stream for this
Authors at Google talk.

00:00:08.790 --> 00:00:11.582
And I could not be
more excited to be

00:00:11.582 --> 00:00:12.790
introducing our guests today.

00:00:12.790 --> 00:00:14.160
So I'll read a little
bit to make sure I

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:15.060
don't miss the good stuff.

00:00:15.060 --> 00:00:17.290
Although, there's so much,
we could spend a whole hour

00:00:17.290 --> 00:00:17.430
on this.

00:00:17.430 --> 00:00:19.160
JACK WELCH: We don't
need to do that.

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:19.740
LASZLO BOCK: Just a little.

00:00:19.740 --> 00:00:20.050
Just a little.

00:00:20.050 --> 00:00:21.270
Some people may not
have heard of you two.

00:00:21.270 --> 00:00:21.894
JACK WELCH: OK.

00:00:21.894 --> 00:00:23.899
LASZLO BOCK: So just in case.

00:00:23.899 --> 00:00:25.940
We're thrilled to host
Jack and Suzy Welch today.

00:00:25.940 --> 00:00:28.170
Jack was chairman and
CEO of General Electric

00:00:28.170 --> 00:00:30.410
during a revolutionary
time in its history,

00:00:30.410 --> 00:00:32.240
a time when it went
from a great company

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:34.500
to the greatest company.

00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:37.080
And the management practices
that Jack instilled

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:39.820
and the team he built have
been lauded ever since.

00:00:39.820 --> 00:00:43.140
And it's a once in a generation
kind of company, an institution

00:00:43.140 --> 00:00:45.680
that he built and created.

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:48.000
Suzy, an author and journalist,
former editor-in-chief

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:49.740
of "The Harvard
Business Review,"

00:00:49.740 --> 00:00:55.326
a keen judge of people and
talent, and a fantastic writer.

00:00:55.326 --> 00:00:56.950
They've been partners
and collaborators

00:00:56.950 --> 00:00:58.477
for over a decade.

00:00:58.477 --> 00:01:00.560
They're both involved in
the Jack Welch Management

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:03.450
Institute, which is a
leadership development

00:01:03.450 --> 00:01:05.740
program and an online
MBA program as well.

00:01:05.740 --> 00:01:07.281
And they're here to
speak to us today

00:01:07.281 --> 00:01:09.690
about their book, "The
Real Life MBA: Your no

00:01:09.690 --> 00:01:12.490
BS guide to winning the
game, building a team,

00:01:12.490 --> 00:01:14.370
and growing your career."

00:01:14.370 --> 00:01:16.800
And everything that
you talk about in here

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:19.010
resonates incredibly deeply.

00:01:19.010 --> 00:01:20.700
It's a personal
thrill, actually,

00:01:20.700 --> 00:01:23.230
to be here because of my
own history, my few minutes

00:01:23.230 --> 00:01:27.230
I spent at GE, unfortunately
after your tenure.

00:01:27.230 --> 00:01:30.430
And it's a delight to meet
you in person as well, Suzy.

00:01:30.430 --> 00:01:34.370
So as you can see, I had a
lot of comments and questions.

00:01:34.370 --> 00:01:36.290
So what we do is
I'd kick things off,

00:01:36.290 --> 00:01:37.950
and then we'll open
it up to questions.

00:01:37.950 --> 00:01:40.090
We also have an online page
where people online are

00:01:40.090 --> 00:01:41.506
submitting questions,
and somebody

00:01:41.506 --> 00:01:43.150
will come up and tee those up.

00:01:43.150 --> 00:01:44.226
JACK WELCH: Great.

00:01:44.226 --> 00:01:46.100
LASZLO BOCK: And I have
the advantage in that

00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:47.350
I've read this cover to cover.

00:01:47.350 --> 00:01:51.670
I don't know if everybody in the
room has yet had a chance to.

00:01:51.670 --> 00:01:53.730
But just for a context
setting question,

00:01:53.730 --> 00:01:56.070
it's been about 20 years
since you've been at GE,

00:01:56.070 --> 00:01:59.170
and you two have been partners
in crime for some time.

00:01:59.170 --> 00:02:00.340
What have you been up to?

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:01.910
What have you been doing?

00:02:01.910 --> 00:02:07.030
JACK WELCH: Traveling the world,
selling a message of business.

00:02:07.030 --> 00:02:08.550
Business is good.

00:02:08.550 --> 00:02:10.060
Winning is good.

00:02:10.060 --> 00:02:13.340
When companies win,
good things happen.

00:02:13.340 --> 00:02:15.620
You get a cheerful crowd
like this in the room

00:02:15.620 --> 00:02:16.740
because Google wins.

00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:19.980
You wouldn't have that
if it was in the tank.

00:02:19.980 --> 00:02:23.360
So basically we're out
selling how to make it win

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:25.420
and why winning is good.

00:02:25.420 --> 00:02:30.550
And we're also running 24
private equity companies.

00:02:30.550 --> 00:02:35.590
And we started a school,
which now has 900 MBAs.

00:02:35.590 --> 00:02:37.920
We've spoken to over a
million and a quarter people.

00:02:37.920 --> 00:02:38.790
Excuse my voice.

00:02:38.790 --> 00:02:41.430
I've been doing this
for three weeks.

00:02:41.430 --> 00:02:46.080
And I'm a burned out guy
now, but I love doing it.

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:47.994
We both love doing it,
and we learn every day

00:02:47.994 --> 00:02:48.910
from different people.

00:02:48.910 --> 00:02:50.640
We've been in the Midwest.

00:02:50.640 --> 00:02:52.317
We've been across
the East Coast.

00:02:52.317 --> 00:02:54.150
And then we've been in
this beautiful bubble

00:02:54.150 --> 00:02:56.106
called California.

00:02:56.106 --> 00:02:57.480
LASZLO BOCK: Now,
you were saying

00:02:57.480 --> 00:02:59.564
when we were talking before
that what you see here

00:02:59.564 --> 00:03:02.063
in Silicon Valley-- and you've
been to some other companies.

00:03:02.063 --> 00:03:03.160
You've talked to folks.

00:03:03.160 --> 00:03:06.269
You were both telling me
it's a little different from

00:03:06.269 --> 00:03:08.810
once you get 50 miles from here,
once you get in the Midwest,

00:03:08.810 --> 00:03:09.893
once you get to the South.

00:03:09.893 --> 00:03:11.273
What are you seeing everywhere?

00:03:11.273 --> 00:03:12.075
How's it different?

00:03:12.075 --> 00:03:13.700
JACK WELCH: Well,
it's a tougher grind.

00:03:13.700 --> 00:03:14.730
It's a tougher grind.

00:03:14.730 --> 00:03:19.490
Since the 2008 recession, things
have gotten a lot tougher.

00:03:19.490 --> 00:03:23.690
And people out there aren't
back to employment levels

00:03:23.690 --> 00:03:26.770
they were at before.

00:03:26.770 --> 00:03:31.020
They're not sure that the
company that they signed up for

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:32.270
is still the same company.

00:03:32.270 --> 00:03:33.590
They've lost some benefits.

00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:35.490
Some other things
have gone away.

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:37.090
Companies have shrunk down.

00:03:37.090 --> 00:03:41.570
The word across most of the
country is do more with less.

00:03:41.570 --> 00:03:42.420
That's the slogan.

00:03:42.420 --> 00:03:44.209
No matter where you
go, do more with less.

00:03:44.209 --> 00:03:45.250
It's not the slogan here.

00:03:46.929 --> 00:03:48.470
SUZY WELCH: This
morning when we were

00:03:48.470 --> 00:03:51.610
getting ready to come here--
we've been here for a few days,

00:03:51.610 --> 00:03:54.080
and obviously we in
our lives had dealings

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:55.610
with Silicon Valley companies.

00:03:55.610 --> 00:03:58.010
And I just was ruminating.

00:03:58.010 --> 00:04:01.041
And I said to Jack, it is really
like a different planet here.

00:04:01.041 --> 00:04:02.540
We've just been
through the Midwest,

00:04:02.540 --> 00:04:04.210
Kansas City, Minneapolis.

00:04:04.210 --> 00:04:06.074
And just the questions
are different,

00:04:06.074 --> 00:04:07.490
and the expressions
are different.

00:04:07.490 --> 00:04:10.170
And it's like this
very-- and I'm

00:04:10.170 --> 00:04:12.690
saying this in the most
positive way, because it's

00:04:12.690 --> 00:04:13.440
a beautiful thing.

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:15.000
But it's a very
shiny, happy place

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.750
compared to many other
pockets in the United States.

00:04:18.750 --> 00:04:22.710
Where the sense of
possibility here is amazing,

00:04:22.710 --> 00:04:25.190
but we've been in rooms
filled with people

00:04:25.190 --> 00:04:28.680
who have a very different
sense of what the world feels

00:04:28.680 --> 00:04:30.909
like right now.

00:04:30.909 --> 00:04:32.825
And wouldn't it be an
amazing, marvelous thing

00:04:32.825 --> 00:04:34.550
if the whole country
was experiencing

00:04:34.550 --> 00:04:35.740
what you're experiencing?

00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:36.410
It's great.

00:04:36.410 --> 00:04:39.010
JACK WELCH: The best way to
think about this is Google

00:04:39.010 --> 00:04:42.022
runs a survey every quarter.

00:04:42.022 --> 00:04:42.980
SUZY WELCH: Not Google.

00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:43.938
JACK WELCH: Not Google.

00:04:43.938 --> 00:04:45.850
I mean Gallop runs
a-- I'm at Google,

00:04:45.850 --> 00:04:47.360
so I got Google on the brain.

00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:50.980
LASZLO BOCK: We do surveys
every quarter, too.

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:53.200
JACK WELCH: Gallop does
a survey every quarter

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:56.820
on employee
engagement in America.

00:04:56.820 --> 00:05:00.660
And in the recession,
it got down to the point

00:05:00.660 --> 00:05:06.020
where 70%, in 2008, of employees
didn't like going to work,

00:05:06.020 --> 00:05:10.220
were not engaged in their job,
didn't like what was going on.

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:13.700
Today, six years later,
seven years later,

00:05:13.700 --> 00:05:16.355
it's 65% in the
last quarter that

00:05:16.355 --> 00:05:17.780
are disengaged with their work.

00:05:17.780 --> 00:05:18.840
They don't like work.

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:20.710
Work isn't part of their life.

00:05:20.710 --> 00:05:22.440
They don't see it as
part of their life.

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:24.740
It's a way to get a check.

00:05:24.740 --> 00:05:27.486
And that's a terrible thing.

00:05:27.486 --> 00:05:29.110
And so we're out
trying to change that.

00:05:29.110 --> 00:05:31.620
We're out trying to get
people to have this feeling

00:05:31.620 --> 00:05:33.240
of excitement, about growth.

00:05:33.240 --> 00:05:34.210
Growth is an elixir.

00:05:34.210 --> 00:05:37.250
And what you can do to grow,
how you can grow, how you get

00:05:37.250 --> 00:05:39.230
aligned-- all these things.

00:05:39.230 --> 00:05:42.780
We think-- and we've seen
it in private equity.

00:05:42.780 --> 00:05:45.770
I've been involved with 74
companies over the last 15

00:05:45.770 --> 00:05:48.680
years, 24 are active now.

00:05:48.680 --> 00:05:50.570
And we've changed lives
at these companies,

00:05:50.570 --> 00:05:53.760
because these companies were
orphans in big companies.

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:55.030
They were broken companies.

00:05:55.030 --> 00:05:58.330
You don't buy a private equity
company because it's healthy.

00:05:58.330 --> 00:06:01.050
You buy a sick company
and try and fix it.

00:06:01.050 --> 00:06:02.880
And you spend several
years fixing it,

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:04.620
and then giving it freedom.

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:09.090
But that life is not going
on in many companies.

00:06:09.090 --> 00:06:12.140
LASZLO BOCK: But you
started out by saying

00:06:12.140 --> 00:06:14.500
you're about preaching winning.

00:06:14.500 --> 00:06:17.206
And you famously are
known for-- at GE,

00:06:17.206 --> 00:06:19.205
you said you have to be
number one or number two

00:06:19.205 --> 00:06:21.690
in an industry,
or get out of it.

00:06:21.690 --> 00:06:24.000
You talk about the importance
of growth, of winning.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.520
What you write about here and
what you're hinting at now

00:06:26.520 --> 00:06:28.810
is people just not
enjoying their work,

00:06:28.810 --> 00:06:30.060
about there not being meaning.

00:06:30.060 --> 00:06:31.976
And in the book, you
talk about the importance

00:06:31.976 --> 00:06:33.170
of having a mission.

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:35.114
Is a mission the
same as winning?

00:06:35.114 --> 00:06:36.030
Is winning sufficient?

00:06:36.030 --> 00:06:37.571
Or is there something
bigger, better?

00:06:37.571 --> 00:06:38.970
JACK WELCH:
Winning's the product

00:06:38.970 --> 00:06:41.970
of a good mission, and
a good set of behaviors,

00:06:41.970 --> 00:06:44.040
and the consequences
that come from it.

00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:49.710
So winning is the result.
It's not a starting point.

00:06:49.710 --> 00:06:52.200
Like, for example, we say
the chief characteristic

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:55.210
of a leader is to be a
chief meaning officer.

00:06:55.210 --> 00:06:57.091
Give the work purpose.

00:06:57.091 --> 00:06:59.090
People come to work because
they want a purpose.

00:06:59.090 --> 00:07:01.150
They want to have
a reason for being.

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:02.880
They want to be a part of it.

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:07.830
And your job as a
leader is to let people

00:07:07.830 --> 00:07:09.610
know why they're
there, where they're

00:07:09.610 --> 00:07:12.450
going, why they're going there.

00:07:12.450 --> 00:07:14.170
And then when
everybody leaves out

00:07:14.170 --> 00:07:17.730
in most places, what's in
it for them to go there?

00:07:17.730 --> 00:07:21.476
And what are the consequences,
pro and con, of doing it right?

00:07:21.476 --> 00:07:23.350
LASZLO BOCK: But how do
you find that meaning

00:07:23.350 --> 00:07:25.683
in the kind of places you've
been to over the last week?

00:07:25.683 --> 00:07:28.020
SUZY WELCH: I'm just think
about these two anecdotes.

00:07:28.020 --> 00:07:29.620
I hear your
question, and this is

00:07:29.620 --> 00:07:31.620
a little bit of a roundabout
way of saying this.

00:07:31.620 --> 00:07:34.210
For many years
after Jack retired,

00:07:34.210 --> 00:07:37.610
we ran a seminar called
"Two Days with Jack Welch."

00:07:37.610 --> 00:07:40.460
Where 100 CEOs would come
in from around the world,

00:07:40.460 --> 00:07:43.130
and they would work
with Jack for two days.

00:07:43.130 --> 00:07:45.770
And when we first did the
planning for this Jack said,

00:07:45.770 --> 00:07:47.850
I'm just going to
spend the first hour

00:07:47.850 --> 00:07:49.680
on just talking about mission.

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:51.250
Because all these
CEOs surely know

00:07:51.250 --> 00:07:53.040
what the mission is
of their company,

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:55.810
and then we'll move
right on to X, Y, and Z.

00:07:55.810 --> 00:07:59.310
So the first day starts out,
and Jack looks at this crowd--

00:07:59.310 --> 00:08:02.324
100 CEOs who had self-selected
to come to a group

00:08:02.324 --> 00:08:03.240
to work on management.

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:05.125
So you'd think they'd
be very self-actualized

00:08:05.125 --> 00:08:06.320
and enlightened.

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:09.010
And I was sitting at one
table with a bunch of CEOs,

00:08:09.010 --> 00:08:10.930
so I could hear what
they were saying.

00:08:10.930 --> 00:08:14.100
And Jack said, OK, so just
jot down your mission.

00:08:14.100 --> 00:08:18.020
And there was this weird,
uncomfortable silence.

00:08:18.020 --> 00:08:19.600
And I was actually
sitting at a table

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:22.390
with two brothers who were
co-CEOs of a family company.

00:08:22.390 --> 00:08:25.530
And one brother said to the
other, what's our mission?

00:08:25.530 --> 00:08:27.880
And you're here.

00:08:27.880 --> 00:08:28.560
We've been here.

00:08:28.560 --> 00:08:31.270
We've been at Google an hour
and a half or something.

00:08:31.270 --> 00:08:33.409
I've heard the mission
mentioned repeatedly.

00:08:33.409 --> 00:08:34.530
We got a demo.

00:08:34.530 --> 00:08:35.799
We met people in the hallway.

00:08:35.799 --> 00:08:37.640
And the mission is just
flowing all out of you,

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:38.490
and I actually think you also--

00:08:38.490 --> 00:08:40.079
LASZLO BOCK: Are you
getting sick of it by now?

00:08:40.079 --> 00:08:41.745
SUZY WELCH: No, I
actually dig it a lot.

00:08:41.745 --> 00:08:44.300
I was saying to Jack, too bad
none of our kids are engineers.

00:08:44.300 --> 00:08:46.495
They know poetry and whatever.

00:08:46.495 --> 00:08:47.870
Because this is
the kind of place

00:08:47.870 --> 00:08:49.370
a mother would want
her kid to work.

00:08:49.370 --> 00:08:53.660
And so because of that mission
and that sense of incredible--

00:08:53.660 --> 00:08:55.670
I think you all know
what you're doing here

00:08:55.670 --> 00:08:58.400
and how your work is
connected to the mission.

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:02.020
And secondly, in
our 10, 12 years

00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:05.040
traveling around
the world, we've

00:09:05.040 --> 00:09:07.130
made the point
over and over again

00:09:07.130 --> 00:09:09.860
that it's imperative
for leaders, no matter

00:09:09.860 --> 00:09:12.100
if you're a leader of 300
people or three people,

00:09:12.100 --> 00:09:15.270
to make sure that your
people know where they stand.

00:09:15.270 --> 00:09:17.434
How they're doing, what
they're doing well,

00:09:17.434 --> 00:09:19.600
what they could be doing
better, what the trajectory

00:09:19.600 --> 00:09:21.250
of their career looks like.

00:09:21.250 --> 00:09:26.670
And when we travel around we
say to crowds, how many of you

00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:27.950
know where you stand?

00:09:27.950 --> 00:09:32.620
And it is a very, very good
day when 15% of the crowd

00:09:32.620 --> 00:09:33.500
raises their hands.

00:09:33.500 --> 00:09:35.970
We were in Chicago
the other day.

00:09:35.970 --> 00:09:37.710
600 people we asked
this question.

00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:39.960
Four people raised their
hands, knew where they stood.

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:41.360
It was a big business group.

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:44.857
And so they didn't know
the meaning of their work.

00:09:44.857 --> 00:09:47.190
Clearly, if you're not having
a conversation about where

00:09:47.190 --> 00:09:49.065
you stand and what you
could be doing better,

00:09:49.065 --> 00:09:51.360
you don't even know what
the meaning of your work is.

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:55.134
This is why that number is
65% of people disengaged.

00:09:55.134 --> 00:09:56.550
So you should all
pinch yourselves

00:09:56.550 --> 00:09:58.571
because I bet you
know where you stand.

00:09:58.571 --> 00:10:00.820
And we did this yesterday
at a Silicon Valley company,

00:10:00.820 --> 00:10:02.180
and 85% of the hands went up.

00:10:02.180 --> 00:10:03.730
JACK WELCH: No,
it was about 60%.

00:10:03.730 --> 00:10:04.490
SUZY WELCH: But it
was still better

00:10:04.490 --> 00:10:05.230
than any place we've been.

00:10:05.230 --> 00:10:07.430
JACK WELCH: Any place we've
been Do you want to try it here?

00:10:07.430 --> 00:10:08.555
LASZLO BOCK: Oh no, no, no.

00:10:08.555 --> 00:10:09.660
I'm terrified.

00:10:09.660 --> 00:10:12.140
Do not.

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:12.939
We can try it.

00:10:12.939 --> 00:10:13.980
SUZY WELCH: Let's try it.

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:15.021
LASZLO BOCK: Let's do it.

00:10:15.021 --> 00:10:17.810
JACK WELCH: How many people
here know what their boss thinks

00:10:17.810 --> 00:10:20.670
of them, they know
exactly where they stand,

00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:24.410
and what their
career trajectory is?

00:10:24.410 --> 00:10:25.370
LASZLO BOCK: Come on.

00:10:25.370 --> 00:10:25.500
Thank god.

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:25.810
Thank god.

00:10:25.810 --> 00:10:26.643
SUZY WELCH: You win.

00:10:28.690 --> 00:10:30.350
JACK WELCH: Well, I'd say 60%.

00:10:30.350 --> 00:10:30.590
SUZY WELCH: No, no.

00:10:30.590 --> 00:10:31.880
I think a little
bit higher, Jack.

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:32.490
Let's do it again.

00:10:32.490 --> 00:10:32.870
Let's do it again.

00:10:32.870 --> 00:10:34.328
LASZLO BOCK: Looks
like 110% to me.

00:10:37.240 --> 00:10:38.950
It was not 100%.

00:10:38.950 --> 00:10:40.450
There was like four
people in there.

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:42.440
Kevin, I'm looking at you.

00:10:42.440 --> 00:10:43.494
SUZY WELCH: Taking names.

00:10:43.494 --> 00:10:44.910
LASZLO BOCK: No,
but it's actually

00:10:44.910 --> 00:10:46.710
something we're not
always great at,

00:10:46.710 --> 00:10:52.600
because we love-- we focus
on hiring great people.

00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:54.640
And then we try to give
them a lot of freedom.

00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:55.750
And we try to get
managers great.

00:10:55.750 --> 00:10:57.791
But it's a hard thing even
for us to get managers

00:10:57.791 --> 00:10:59.160
to have those tough messages.

00:10:59.160 --> 00:11:01.090
And later in the book,
you talk about this.

00:11:01.090 --> 00:11:03.780
You have a section-- I'm going
to skip ahead-- where you talk

00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:05.640
about a woman named Lauren.

00:11:05.640 --> 00:11:07.010
Lauren is a financial analyst.

00:11:07.010 --> 00:11:08.190
She's 34.

00:11:08.190 --> 00:11:10.830
She'd heard whispers that she
might be made a partner as part

00:11:10.830 --> 00:11:12.510
of a management transition.

00:11:12.510 --> 00:11:13.610
And you go on.

00:11:13.610 --> 00:11:15.260
But suddenly the
whispers stopped,

00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:17.130
and Lauren was
informed by a colleague

00:11:17.130 --> 00:11:18.970
that her boss was the reason.

00:11:18.970 --> 00:11:20.820
And you continue on.

00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:22.547
And eventually
Lauren was asked--

00:11:22.547 --> 00:11:24.130
we asked Lauren--
you two asked Lauren

00:11:24.130 --> 00:11:26.890
if her boss felt the same way
about her value to the firm

00:11:26.890 --> 00:11:28.800
as she felt about her
value to the firm.

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:30.360
And she said, he
just doesn't want

00:11:30.360 --> 00:11:31.984
me to be a partner
because I'm a woman.

00:11:31.984 --> 00:11:35.030
He got pissed off when I went
to part time after my baby.

00:11:35.030 --> 00:11:37.030
And you write,
was that the case?

00:11:37.030 --> 00:11:38.480
It's possible.

00:11:38.480 --> 00:11:39.580
But here's the story.

00:11:39.580 --> 00:11:41.150
Lauren was guessing.

00:11:41.150 --> 00:11:42.670
When we pressed
her, she admitted

00:11:42.670 --> 00:11:44.940
she had no clue
how her boss really

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:47.530
felt about her performance
long before her baby

00:11:47.530 --> 00:11:50.690
or after, because
he'd never told her.

00:11:50.690 --> 00:11:52.060
And so that makes me wonder.

00:11:52.060 --> 00:11:55.650
And it's great that we
actually weren't quite at 100%.

00:11:55.650 --> 00:11:58.972
Whose job is it to make
sure the employee knows

00:11:58.972 --> 00:11:59.680
where they stand?

00:11:59.680 --> 00:12:01.120
Is it the boss's job?

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:02.230
Is it the employee's job?

00:12:02.230 --> 00:12:03.405
Is it shared 50-50?

00:12:03.405 --> 00:12:05.280
JACK WELCH: No, I think
it's without question

00:12:05.280 --> 00:12:09.110
the boss's job, but the
employee has a responsibility,

00:12:09.110 --> 00:12:12.590
if they've got a bad boss,
to press on about it.

00:12:12.590 --> 00:12:14.740
And we talk about
career purgatories,

00:12:14.740 --> 00:12:16.330
about working for
a boss that doesn't

00:12:16.330 --> 00:12:18.350
have your interests at heart.

00:12:18.350 --> 00:12:20.050
That happens in
every good company.

00:12:20.050 --> 00:12:20.680
It'll happen.

00:12:20.680 --> 00:12:22.240
You'll get a bad boss.

00:12:22.240 --> 00:12:25.480
We talk about bosses that
don't have the generosity gene.

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:27.510
That aren't generous
about their praise,

00:12:27.510 --> 00:12:31.150
generous about their rewards,
steal ideas and take them up

00:12:31.150 --> 00:12:33.140
as their own-- all those things.

00:12:33.140 --> 00:12:35.660
So you've got to put
timetables on those situations.

00:12:35.660 --> 00:12:37.750
But it really is the boss's job.

00:12:37.750 --> 00:12:38.590
We have a daughter.

00:12:38.590 --> 00:12:41.580
You might tell this
story, this one story.

00:12:41.580 --> 00:12:43.640
SUZY WELCH: So one of our
daughters works in LA.

00:12:43.640 --> 00:12:45.340
And she's in the
entertainment business

00:12:45.340 --> 00:12:48.270
where she was very
happy to get a job.

00:12:48.270 --> 00:12:51.860
So she's working
away, and you can

00:12:51.860 --> 00:12:54.340
imagine having your career
managed from afar by us, right?

00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:56.010
So she actually
is working in LA,

00:12:56.010 --> 00:12:58.300
and she doesn't know
how she's doing.

00:12:58.300 --> 00:13:01.180
She's working very,
very hard, but her sense

00:13:01.180 --> 00:13:04.290
of her performance rises and
falls on her boss's mood, OK?

00:13:04.290 --> 00:13:06.040
So he's in a good mood,
she's doing great.

00:13:06.040 --> 00:13:07.540
JACK WELCH: And we
get a phone call.

00:13:07.540 --> 00:13:09.372
If the boss grunts,
we get a phone call.

00:13:09.372 --> 00:13:11.080
SUZY WELCH: The phone
calls and the texts

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:12.380
are related to his mood.

00:13:12.380 --> 00:13:17.270
So then one day, she
gets a raise in the mail,

00:13:17.270 --> 00:13:18.010
in her paycheck.

00:13:18.010 --> 00:13:20.750
And she calls us, and
she's ecstatic, second

00:13:20.750 --> 00:13:22.750
only to us being ecstatic,
that she got a raise.

00:13:22.750 --> 00:13:23.560
And she said, I got a raise.

00:13:23.560 --> 00:13:24.143
I got a raise.

00:13:24.143 --> 00:13:25.980
We said, well, why
did you get the raise?

00:13:25.980 --> 00:13:27.820
And she doesn't
have any idea why.

00:13:27.820 --> 00:13:30.060
So because she's related
to us, we said to her,

00:13:30.060 --> 00:13:32.310
you have to go in and find
out why you got this raise.

00:13:32.310 --> 00:13:32.670
No, no.

00:13:32.670 --> 00:13:33.650
I don't want to piss him off.

00:13:33.650 --> 00:13:35.899
We said, you've got to find
out why you got the raise.

00:13:35.899 --> 00:13:38.030
So finally under
extreme pressure,

00:13:38.030 --> 00:13:39.480
she went in, into his office.

00:13:39.480 --> 00:13:42.449
We can only imagine it was
like, hi, sorry to bother you.

00:13:42.449 --> 00:13:43.740
And so she said, I got a raise.

00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:45.080
I'm really happy.

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:47.650
Can you tell me why?

00:13:47.650 --> 00:13:52.153
And he looked at her,
and said to her, merit.

00:13:52.153 --> 00:13:52.860
Period.

00:13:52.860 --> 00:13:53.410
That's it.

00:13:53.410 --> 00:13:54.960
JACK WELCH: And what
do you do with that?

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:55.460
SUZY WELCH: And she
ran out the door.

00:13:55.460 --> 00:13:57.060
She was so happy to get
an answer and call us

00:13:57.060 --> 00:13:57.893
and say, guess what?

00:13:57.893 --> 00:13:59.566
I got a raise as a merit!

00:13:59.566 --> 00:14:01.540
And she still doesn't
know what it was.

00:14:01.540 --> 00:14:03.600
Now, since then,
she's been promoted.

00:14:03.600 --> 00:14:06.450
So clearly they're happy
with her performance.

00:14:06.450 --> 00:14:09.220
But right now all she knows
about what she does well

00:14:09.220 --> 00:14:10.534
is "merit."

00:14:10.534 --> 00:14:11.950
LASZLO BOCK: So
what's your advice

00:14:11.950 --> 00:14:15.210
then to somebody who's got a
bad boss, who's not telling you

00:14:15.210 --> 00:14:15.900
where you stand.

00:14:15.900 --> 00:14:17.510
Just that you're
fine, you're fine.

00:14:17.510 --> 00:14:18.590
Your bonus is kind of OK.

00:14:18.590 --> 00:14:19.090
It's great.

00:14:19.090 --> 00:14:22.980
Maybe it goes up a little
each year, whatever.

00:14:22.980 --> 00:14:24.190
Do you confront the boss?

00:14:24.190 --> 00:14:24.990
Do you push for an answer?

00:14:24.990 --> 00:14:25.455
What's your advice?

00:14:25.455 --> 00:14:27.205
JACK WELCH: No, I think
the way you go is,

00:14:27.205 --> 00:14:31.730
I'd like to talk to you about
how you feel about my work.

00:14:31.730 --> 00:14:32.590
How do you feel?

00:14:32.590 --> 00:14:35.020
What do you think
I'm doing well?

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:36.740
And how do you
think I can improve?

00:14:36.740 --> 00:14:38.380
How can I really improve?

00:14:38.380 --> 00:14:40.690
Because I want to do
a better job here.

00:14:40.690 --> 00:14:44.250
And you don't ever
confront them head on.

00:14:44.250 --> 00:14:45.790
You go with what
can I do better?

00:14:45.790 --> 00:14:46.540
LASZLO BOCK: Wait.

00:14:46.540 --> 00:14:48.040
Why don't you
confront them head on?

00:14:48.040 --> 00:14:50.232
Why don't you just say,
what's going on with me?

00:14:50.232 --> 00:14:52.190
JACK WELCH: Well, you
can say, what's going on?

00:14:52.190 --> 00:14:54.420
But you've got to ask
them, what can I do better?

00:14:54.420 --> 00:14:56.060
Don't go in and start
challenging them.

00:14:56.060 --> 00:14:57.130
It doesn't make sense.

00:14:57.130 --> 00:14:57.920
It's suicide.

00:14:57.920 --> 00:15:00.552
LASZLO BOCK: Yeah.

00:15:00.552 --> 00:15:02.260
JACK WELCH: But come
at it the other way.

00:15:02.260 --> 00:15:03.410
How can I do better?

00:15:03.410 --> 00:15:06.840
And what do you think I
have to do to move on?

00:15:06.840 --> 00:15:10.000
What do you think would
be the criteria that

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.140
would get me the next level?

00:15:12.140 --> 00:15:12.890
LASZLO BOCK: Yeah.

00:15:12.890 --> 00:15:15.090
Well, the two of you, you
talk about later in the book

00:15:15.090 --> 00:15:16.320
when you're into
the personal advice.

00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:18.239
You have a section called
"Why Careers Stall,"

00:15:18.239 --> 00:15:19.280
which is related to this.

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:22.381
Because often your career
stalls, probably you also often

00:15:22.381 --> 00:15:23.380
aren't getting feedback.

00:15:23.380 --> 00:15:24.890
And you're trying
to figure it out.

00:15:24.890 --> 00:15:27.900
And you talk about careers
stalling for a few reasons.

00:15:27.900 --> 00:15:29.520
You've got a blocker above you.

00:15:29.520 --> 00:15:30.830
You can't grow.

00:15:30.830 --> 00:15:33.430
You talk about how
to resolve that.

00:15:33.430 --> 00:15:35.510
You talk about
wrongheaded notions

00:15:35.510 --> 00:15:38.970
about the importance of
multifunctional expertise.

00:15:38.970 --> 00:15:43.380
You talk about boss haters,
and you talk about purgatory.

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:45.855
It's like Dante's "Inferno"
of career management here.

00:15:45.855 --> 00:15:46.760
It's awful.

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:51.810
So can you talk a little bit
about-- if you feel stuck,

00:15:51.810 --> 00:15:52.775
what is a blocker?

00:15:52.775 --> 00:15:55.400
What does that look like-- ahead
of you, above you, around you?

00:15:55.400 --> 00:15:56.570
And how we can step
through each of these.

00:15:56.570 --> 00:15:57.944
JACK WELCH: A
blocker is somebody

00:15:57.944 --> 00:16:03.190
who's enjoying your great work,
and is very happy to keep you

00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:06.270
in the draw to keep
getting all that good work,

00:16:06.270 --> 00:16:08.330
so that they look very good.

00:16:08.330 --> 00:16:10.030
That could be one
case of a blocker.

00:16:10.030 --> 00:16:13.310
Another case of blocker is--
and these Midwestern companies

00:16:13.310 --> 00:16:15.750
we were talking about
is-- there's no growth.

00:16:15.750 --> 00:16:17.180
The boss is going nowhere.

00:16:17.180 --> 00:16:18.490
That doesn't happen here.

00:16:18.490 --> 00:16:20.899
There's plenty of growth
creating opportunities

00:16:20.899 --> 00:16:21.440
all the time.

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:24.250
But in many companies,
most of the world right now

00:16:24.250 --> 00:16:27.650
with a GDP of 0.8%
growth doesn't

00:16:27.650 --> 00:16:30.390
have all these jobs opening up.

00:16:30.390 --> 00:16:33.130
So you're stuck there
in a no-growth situation

00:16:33.130 --> 00:16:35.530
with a good boss maybe.

00:16:35.530 --> 00:16:38.000
But what you have to do
in all these situations

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:39.650
is control your own destiny.

00:16:39.650 --> 00:16:41.850
You've got to put
a timeframe on it.

00:16:41.850 --> 00:16:44.600
I'll stick it out here for
two years, or one year,

00:16:44.600 --> 00:16:46.230
whatever you decide.

00:16:46.230 --> 00:16:49.070
Pick a time frame
and I'll overdeliver.

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:51.570
I'll give them more than
they have ever seen before.

00:16:51.570 --> 00:16:56.120
And if nothing happens, I've got
to take my wares and move on.

00:16:56.120 --> 00:16:59.140
LASZLO BOCK: Why do you
think-- when you say it,

00:16:59.140 --> 00:17:00.410
that's fantastic advice.

00:17:00.410 --> 00:17:01.820
Most people don't do that.

00:17:01.820 --> 00:17:03.720
Why not?

00:17:03.720 --> 00:17:06.530
JACK WELCH: Insecurity,
lack of self-confidence,

00:17:06.530 --> 00:17:09.280
comfortable where they are.

00:17:09.280 --> 00:17:12.300
Or maybe family situations--
kids, can't move,

00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:14.730
they're in high school,
college, whatever.

00:17:14.730 --> 00:17:20.920
SUZY WELCH: Momentum,
inertia, humanity,

00:17:20.920 --> 00:17:22.280
and the fear of the unknown.

00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:23.656
And I think also
sometimes people

00:17:23.656 --> 00:17:25.113
don't do anything
because they have

00:17:25.113 --> 00:17:27.810
this little nagging voice inside
saying maybe the problem is me.

00:17:27.810 --> 00:17:30.710
And it's just much easier not
to look at that piece of it,

00:17:30.710 --> 00:17:33.594
and so they'd rather
just bump along.

00:17:33.594 --> 00:17:35.260
JACK WELCH: I used
to go to Crotonville,

00:17:35.260 --> 00:17:37.260
which is our education place.

00:17:37.260 --> 00:17:39.280
And I would teach every class.

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:42.090
And I would spend three
hours in the class Q&amp;A.

00:17:42.090 --> 00:17:43.910
And then I'd spent
three hours at the bar,

00:17:43.910 --> 00:17:46.030
and I'd learn more
at the bar than I

00:17:46.030 --> 00:17:47.780
did in the teaching program.

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:50.560
But basically what I
would always leave them

00:17:50.560 --> 00:17:56.790
with-- always-- love being
here, love being at GE,

00:17:56.790 --> 00:17:57.880
but be ready to leave.

00:18:01.550 --> 00:18:04.840
So that put the pressure
on the leadership.

00:18:04.840 --> 00:18:07.330
If the leadership wasn't
taking care of you,

00:18:07.330 --> 00:18:10.440
and we started seeing
good people leaving

00:18:10.440 --> 00:18:13.050
in a certain area-- and it
didn't happen very often

00:18:13.050 --> 00:18:14.210
in those days.

00:18:14.210 --> 00:18:15.650
It didn't happen very often.

00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:17.770
But if it did, we knew
we had a bad boss.

00:18:17.770 --> 00:18:21.027
Just like if you have
a plant, a factory--

00:18:21.027 --> 00:18:22.110
we had a lot of factories.

00:18:22.110 --> 00:18:25.500
And when a union showed up,
and a union took a vote,

00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:27.650
and they got a
positive vote-- now,

00:18:27.650 --> 00:18:31.420
we never formed a union in
the 21 years I was there.

00:18:31.420 --> 00:18:33.920
But whenever it
came up for a vote,

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:38.150
we knew we had a
jackass plant manager.

00:18:38.150 --> 00:18:40.110
Because otherwise it
wouldn't get there.

00:18:40.110 --> 00:18:44.240
If you had the right
atmosphere, the right feelings

00:18:44.240 --> 00:18:48.290
in the place, a transparency--
we want transparency.

00:18:48.290 --> 00:18:49.850
Transparency is
the biggest virtue

00:18:49.850 --> 00:18:51.880
you can have in a company.

00:18:51.880 --> 00:18:54.300
And if you have a
transparent spot,

00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:55.980
you won't have unions forming.

00:18:55.980 --> 00:18:58.090
People will think they
have voice anyway.

00:18:58.090 --> 00:18:59.410
They will have voice.

00:18:59.410 --> 00:19:02.790
They only form a
union to get voice,

00:19:02.790 --> 00:19:04.332
because nobody's
listening otherwise.

00:19:04.332 --> 00:19:06.331
LASZLO BOCK: So when you
have these situations--

00:19:06.331 --> 00:19:08.210
and I want to circle
back to the career side,

00:19:08.210 --> 00:19:13.120
but you've both seen
a ton of companies.

00:19:13.120 --> 00:19:15.760
And every time in the book
you talk about a leadership

00:19:15.760 --> 00:19:18.760
transition, you talk
about firing people.

00:19:18.760 --> 00:19:21.210
And this isn't the stack
rank 70/20/10 stuff.

00:19:21.210 --> 00:19:25.530
You talk about Eric
Fyrwald at Nalco.

00:19:25.530 --> 00:19:27.830
And he goes in, and he moved on.

00:19:27.830 --> 00:19:29.430
You say many top
leaders had to be

00:19:29.430 --> 00:19:32.080
asked to move on-- more
than half of the top 100

00:19:32.080 --> 00:19:35.412
So new CEO, 50% or more
of the people gone.

00:19:35.412 --> 00:19:37.370
And then you say a
personnel move speaks louder

00:19:37.370 --> 00:19:38.500
than 100 speeches.

00:19:38.500 --> 00:19:39.705
And there's a few other
parts of the book where

00:19:39.705 --> 00:19:41.520
you talk about the
importance of when

00:19:41.520 --> 00:19:45.690
you come in as a leader firing
some of the people under you.

00:19:45.690 --> 00:19:47.190
Is that just good hygiene?

00:19:47.190 --> 00:19:49.460
JACK WELCH: We're talking
there about private equity.

00:19:49.460 --> 00:19:50.460
LASZLO BOCK: OK.

00:19:50.460 --> 00:19:51.834
JACK WELCH: So in
private equity,

00:19:51.834 --> 00:19:54.580
the reason why you
buy a company is

00:19:54.580 --> 00:19:57.250
it's an orphan,
usually, in a company.

00:19:57.250 --> 00:19:59.747
It's a division
that isn't liked.

00:19:59.747 --> 00:20:02.330
I'm not sure at Google there are
some, but I'll bet there are.

00:20:02.330 --> 00:20:04.820
A division that's
the turkey over here.

00:20:04.820 --> 00:20:07.270
It gets less attention
from the top people.

00:20:07.270 --> 00:20:09.270
It doesn't get loved.

00:20:09.270 --> 00:20:13.160
It doesn't get enough
resources compared to others.

00:20:13.160 --> 00:20:14.840
There are those
in most companies.

00:20:14.840 --> 00:20:18.200
So you buy these companies
because the company

00:20:18.200 --> 00:20:21.560
wants to trim down, particularly
with activists out there now.

00:20:21.560 --> 00:20:23.795
Companies are selling
off divisions,

00:20:23.795 --> 00:20:24.795
and you grab a division.

00:20:24.795 --> 00:20:28.500
Well, those people haven't
been looked at for 10 years.

00:20:28.500 --> 00:20:31.110
They've been sitting
over there, not growing,

00:20:31.110 --> 00:20:34.930
not performing, but not
being told anything.

00:20:34.930 --> 00:20:38.670
So you bring them in, and
you've got to get a fresh eye,

00:20:38.670 --> 00:20:40.110
look at the situation.

00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:42.470
So we're talking
mainly about companies

00:20:42.470 --> 00:20:46.495
you're acquiring that have been
dead on their feet for years.

00:20:46.495 --> 00:20:48.120
SUZY WELCH: And I
think a lot of times,

00:20:48.120 --> 00:20:50.690
and especially in
those stories, when

00:20:50.690 --> 00:20:54.340
you want your company to
be productive, and fast,

00:20:54.340 --> 00:20:57.970
and creative, and innovative,
and all those things,

00:20:57.970 --> 00:21:00.280
people pretty much need
to share the values.

00:21:00.280 --> 00:21:05.880
And the values have to
be things like teamwork,

00:21:05.880 --> 00:21:07.720
and like maybe you have
here, fast failure.

00:21:07.720 --> 00:21:11.470
You have values that you
want people to demonstrate.

00:21:11.470 --> 00:21:13.605
And so when there are these
leadership transitions,

00:21:13.605 --> 00:21:15.480
if a leader comes in
and says, you know what?

00:21:15.480 --> 00:21:18.600
I am installing these values,
the values of urgency,

00:21:18.600 --> 00:21:20.800
and speed, and boundarylessness.

00:21:20.800 --> 00:21:22.360
And you have people
who-- there's

00:21:22.360 --> 00:21:24.670
a great story in
the book, I think,

00:21:24.670 --> 00:21:26.970
when Dave Calhoun
came into Nielsen.

00:21:26.970 --> 00:21:30.166
And he knew that this
was a silo company where

00:21:30.166 --> 00:21:31.290
nobody spoke to each other.

00:21:31.290 --> 00:21:33.130
And he knew that if it was
going to survive and be

00:21:33.130 --> 00:21:34.546
the company he
wanted it to be, he

00:21:34.546 --> 00:21:37.040
needed people who
wanted to share ideas.

00:21:37.040 --> 00:21:40.360
And he tried and tried
to get that value across.

00:21:40.360 --> 00:21:45.320
But when he found managers that
just would not share ideas,

00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:46.590
he had to ask them to move on.

00:21:46.590 --> 00:21:48.390
So it's a lot about values.

00:21:48.390 --> 00:21:49.837
You guys talk
about values a lot,

00:21:49.837 --> 00:21:51.670
so this should sound
pretty familiar, right?

00:21:54.907 --> 00:21:56.990
LASZLO BOCK: Imagine a
company that's going great,

00:21:56.990 --> 00:21:58.870
and you have a leadership
