with just pouring money

00:22:20.250 --> 00:22:22.440
at them, giving them
the resources to grow.

00:22:22.440 --> 00:22:23.860
They were flourishing.

00:22:23.860 --> 00:22:26.880
Now, you rarely find
those birds, OK?

00:22:26.880 --> 00:22:28.740
Whenever you find a
blue bird like that,

00:22:28.740 --> 00:22:30.530
you go home and
rub, rub your hands.

00:22:30.530 --> 00:22:31.720
Life is easy.

00:22:31.720 --> 00:22:32.860
It's all good.

00:22:32.860 --> 00:22:36.965
And you take it public, and
in two years and make 6x.

00:22:36.965 --> 00:22:38.710
LASZLO BOCK: And you
look like a genius.

00:22:38.710 --> 00:22:40.030
JACK WELCH: An absolute genius.

00:22:40.030 --> 00:22:43.250
All you did was give
good people money.

00:22:43.250 --> 00:22:44.750
LASZLO BOCK: That's
a good strategy.

00:22:44.750 --> 00:22:46.327
SUZY WELCH: Yeah.

00:22:46.327 --> 00:22:48.410
JACK WELCH: The thing you
have in your book, which

00:22:48.410 --> 00:22:51.855
I like so much, and I've
never seen it written out.

00:22:51.855 --> 00:22:53.480
I write it all the
time, but I've never

00:22:53.480 --> 00:22:56.370
seen, other than
you and I, this idea

00:22:56.370 --> 00:23:01.320
of paying great people lots.

00:23:01.320 --> 00:23:03.420
Paying great people.

00:23:03.420 --> 00:23:08.510
We have a story in
here of getting whacked

00:23:08.510 --> 00:23:10.890
and recovering from a whack.

00:23:10.890 --> 00:23:15.030
And what we talk about
there is the 2008 Recession.

00:23:15.030 --> 00:23:16.160
We were so brilliant.

00:23:16.160 --> 00:23:19.350
We bought this company
called Home Depot Supply.

00:23:19.350 --> 00:23:22.050
And Home Depot Supply
sold lots of goods

00:23:22.050 --> 00:23:24.460
to the construction industry.

00:23:24.460 --> 00:23:28.010
In 2007, it was booming.

00:23:28.010 --> 00:23:30.440
Housing booming,
everything booming.

00:23:30.440 --> 00:23:34.120
And it was doing $12
billion in revenues.

00:23:34.120 --> 00:23:40.280
In 2008, four quarters later,
it was doing $7 billion.

00:23:40.280 --> 00:23:42.880
It collapsed on itself.

00:23:42.880 --> 00:23:46.140
And so our smart
decision to buy it

00:23:46.140 --> 00:23:48.490
couldn't have been worst timing.

00:23:48.490 --> 00:23:50.630
Could not have
been worse timing.

00:23:50.630 --> 00:23:54.852
We get it, and this guy Joe
D'Angelo brings his team.

00:23:54.852 --> 00:23:56.310
He'd been hiring
them for sometime,

00:23:56.310 --> 00:23:59.640
a bunch of people he
worked with before.

00:23:59.640 --> 00:24:04.400
His first act was not let's
cut 10% across the board.

00:24:04.400 --> 00:24:05.850
We've got to save money.

00:24:05.850 --> 00:24:11.610
No, his first thing was pay
the aces tons of equity,

00:24:11.610 --> 00:24:13.060
tons of equity.

00:24:13.060 --> 00:24:14.930
I've got to keep the stars.

00:24:14.930 --> 00:24:17.490
If I'm going to get out of
this whack, where he's probably

00:24:17.490 --> 00:24:19.780
going bankrupt, the first
thing I've got to do

00:24:19.780 --> 00:24:22.880
is make the stars know we're
all swimming in the same tank

00:24:22.880 --> 00:24:23.750
together.

00:24:23.750 --> 00:24:25.870
And I'm giving
you lots of money.

00:24:25.870 --> 00:24:27.890
Well, to make that
a long story short,

00:24:27.890 --> 00:24:30.620
he did lots of other things
to get out of that whack.

00:24:30.620 --> 00:24:32.330
And we talk about
getting out of a whack.

00:24:32.330 --> 00:24:34.690
We'll all have whacks
business-wise, personal,

00:24:34.690 --> 00:24:37.000
you'll get hit, and
how you get out of it.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:39.530
Well, this is a
story of this guy

00:24:39.530 --> 00:24:42.750
taking the absolute
non-traditional way

00:24:42.750 --> 00:24:43.910
of doing it.

00:24:43.910 --> 00:24:47.950
He went at give me
the aces in the game,

00:24:47.950 --> 00:24:49.840
and I'll give them
all the money.

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:52.460
Well, they just went public
about six months ago.

00:24:52.460 --> 00:24:54.610
The top team-- now,
this isn't big money

00:24:54.610 --> 00:24:57.740
by Silicon Valley
standards, but the top guys

00:24:57.740 --> 00:25:00.530
got over $100 million.

00:25:00.530 --> 00:25:02.234
LASZLO BOCK: That's
big money even here.

00:25:02.234 --> 00:25:03.150
JACK WELCH: Even here?

00:25:03.150 --> 00:25:05.170
LASZLO BOCK: Let me
correct you, yeah.

00:25:05.170 --> 00:25:06.200
That counts.

00:25:06.200 --> 00:25:08.670
JACK WELCH: No, and
the mid-level guys all

00:25:08.670 --> 00:25:10.760
got $20 to $40 million.

00:25:10.760 --> 00:25:13.310
LASZLO BOCK: That's
also big money.

00:25:13.310 --> 00:25:15.160
JACK WELCH: But it was fabulous.

00:25:15.160 --> 00:25:17.580
But they hung in there
through six years

00:25:17.580 --> 00:25:19.190
of fighting that mess.

00:25:19.190 --> 00:25:22.000
But he did the opposite of
what you traditionally see.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:25.220
Nothing's worse than
anything across the board--

00:25:25.220 --> 00:25:30.250
across the board raises,
across the board cuts--

00:25:30.250 --> 00:25:32.910
they're all sinful
things to do in business.

00:25:32.910 --> 00:25:34.020
They're just cowards.

00:25:34.020 --> 00:25:35.780
LASZLO BOCK: Well, we were
talking about this a little

00:25:35.780 --> 00:25:36.280
beforehand.

00:25:36.280 --> 00:25:37.970
So you find your aces.

00:25:37.970 --> 00:25:40.590
You give them the big equity.

00:25:40.590 --> 00:25:42.810
The middle people,
they kind of get it.

00:25:42.810 --> 00:25:43.790
They're worker bees.

00:25:43.790 --> 00:25:44.310
The people at the bottom--

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:45.590
JACK WELCH: But they
get some equity.

00:25:45.590 --> 00:25:46.690
LASZLO BOCK: OK,
they get equity, too.

00:25:46.690 --> 00:25:48.148
What do you do
about the layer just

00:25:48.148 --> 00:25:51.270
below the ones who
get the giant awards?

00:25:51.270 --> 00:25:53.270
JACK WELCH: That's the
toughest layer to manage.

00:25:53.270 --> 00:26:00.100
I We started out with a
system, Bill Conaty and I,

00:26:00.100 --> 00:26:03.512
of going 10, 15, 50, 15, 10.

00:26:03.512 --> 00:26:05.470
LASZLO BOCK: And Bill
Conaty was your head of--

00:26:05.470 --> 00:26:06.620
JACK WELCH: Head of HR.

00:26:06.620 --> 00:26:08.410
And we were partners in this.

00:26:08.410 --> 00:26:10.240
We [? lived ?] people
the whole time.

00:26:10.240 --> 00:26:11.990
That was our whole job in GE.

00:26:11.990 --> 00:26:14.990
We didn't spend a lot
of time on other stuff.

00:26:14.990 --> 00:26:20.440
And the trouble
always came in trying

00:26:20.440 --> 00:26:24.520
to make these
careful slices of 10

00:26:24.520 --> 00:26:27.480
between the top 10
and the next 15.

00:26:27.480 --> 00:26:28.520
We're all humans.

00:26:28.520 --> 00:26:30.190
We're making these
cuts, and we're not

00:26:30.190 --> 00:26:34.320
really that good at making them,
so we piss off the next group.

00:26:34.320 --> 00:26:39.060
So we cut that down to top
20, middle 70, bottom 10

00:26:39.060 --> 00:26:43.520
to try and get a distribution
that looked like this.

00:26:43.520 --> 00:26:46.730
And the biggest
problem you have is

00:26:46.730 --> 00:26:50.150
taking good people in the
middle and telling them

00:26:50.150 --> 00:26:51.130
they're in the middle.

00:26:51.130 --> 00:26:53.930
That by far is the hardest job.

00:26:53.930 --> 00:26:58.730
And so I always erred on pushing
them to the top of the middle

00:26:58.730 --> 00:27:01.840
and getting them as close
as you could to the top.

00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:03.550
LASZLO BOCK: And
they're happy with that?

00:27:03.550 --> 00:27:05.080
They live happily ever
after, or they were just

00:27:05.080 --> 00:27:06.040
slightly less unhappy?

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:09.610
JACK WELCH: You've got to
understand that these ratings

00:27:09.610 --> 00:27:10.680
are a period in time.

00:27:10.680 --> 00:27:13.980
They're not a lifetime sentence.

00:27:13.980 --> 00:27:17.690
I'm in the top 5%.

00:27:17.690 --> 00:27:18.832
Am I there forever?

00:27:18.832 --> 00:27:20.540
No, if you stink,
you'd get out of there.

00:27:20.540 --> 00:27:23.340
And if you're in the
next group, you guys

00:27:23.340 --> 00:27:25.080
have 5, 20, or whatever.

00:27:25.080 --> 00:27:28.502
You've got that five tier thing.

00:27:28.502 --> 00:27:33.650
And people that can move by
performance-- the thing we've

00:27:33.650 --> 00:27:37.140
got to get clear though
on performance-- even you

00:27:37.140 --> 00:27:39.860
in your letter had a
little misunderstanding

00:27:39.860 --> 00:27:42.270
of what our thing was.

00:27:42.270 --> 00:27:45.190
When you're looking at
valuing where people are,

00:27:45.190 --> 00:27:47.880
there are two axes.

00:27:47.880 --> 00:27:53.990
On one axis is behaviors, the
values of the company-- speed,

00:27:53.990 --> 00:27:56.220
boundaryless
behavior, et cetera.

00:27:56.220 --> 00:28:00.770
Now, you do that, a separate
evaluation of these things.

00:28:00.770 --> 00:28:03.140
And you put a half
circle or a full circle,

00:28:03.140 --> 00:28:05.710
because you can't put a
numerical number to those.

00:28:05.710 --> 00:28:07.290
You fill in a circle.

00:28:07.290 --> 00:28:09.160
If they're fully
qualified in that area,

00:28:09.160 --> 00:28:12.030
they get a full circle,
half circle, quarter circle,

00:28:12.030 --> 00:28:12.760
whatever.

00:28:12.760 --> 00:28:14.301
And then you come
up with a judgment.

00:28:14.301 --> 00:28:20.060
This is how this employee
adheres to the behaviors

00:28:20.060 --> 00:28:21.810
we need to win.

00:28:21.810 --> 00:28:24.640
Because it's where we're going.

00:28:24.640 --> 00:28:25.480
That's the mission.

00:28:25.480 --> 00:28:28.100
How we're going to get there,
or the behaviors, and then

00:28:28.100 --> 00:28:29.480
the consequences.

00:28:29.480 --> 00:28:32.010
And then on the
bottom axis you've

00:28:32.010 --> 00:28:35.270
got numerical performance.

00:28:35.270 --> 00:28:38.770
Whether it's sales quotas,
R&amp;D, new products--

00:28:38.770 --> 00:28:42.150
whatever you pick as the
financial measurements.

00:28:42.150 --> 00:28:46.470
Then you draw four
quadrants of people.

00:28:46.470 --> 00:28:51.331
And it's low to high
on each axis, OK?

00:28:51.331 --> 00:28:53.580
Low to high-- I wish we had
a little whiteboard here--

00:28:53.580 --> 00:28:55.790
but low to high.

00:28:55.790 --> 00:29:02.490
In the top right, you've got
high values, high behaviors,

00:29:02.490 --> 00:29:03.370
and high performance.

00:29:03.370 --> 00:29:06.320
That's easy, onward and upward.

00:29:06.320 --> 00:29:10.750
On the bottom left
quadrant, you've

00:29:10.750 --> 00:29:14.280
got low behaviors
and low numbers.

00:29:14.280 --> 00:29:15.740
That's easy, too.

00:29:15.740 --> 00:29:19.920
Give them some time to either
fix it, or they move on.

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:26.620
Then the third type over
here on the upper left.

00:29:26.620 --> 00:29:31.300
You've got low performance but
high behaviors-- very good.

00:29:31.300 --> 00:29:32.260
They're on your team.

00:29:32.260 --> 00:29:34.310
They believe in
everything you believe in.

00:29:34.310 --> 00:29:38.040
You give them a second,
third, fourth chance.

00:29:38.040 --> 00:29:39.770
Because when you
get somebody who

00:29:39.770 --> 00:29:43.130
buys into the whole system,
the mission, if you will,

00:29:43.130 --> 00:29:47.880
the mission of Google, the
mission of company X, Y, or Z.

00:29:47.880 --> 00:29:50.630
You want that person.

00:29:50.630 --> 00:29:53.140
But it's the fourth
quadrant out to the right

00:29:53.140 --> 00:29:54.540
that kills companies.

00:29:54.540 --> 00:29:57.010
And I'm sure you've
seen them here,

00:29:57.010 --> 00:29:58.470
and you've see them everywhere.

00:29:58.470 --> 00:30:02.310
The high performer
who's a horse's ass.

00:30:02.310 --> 00:30:05.780
And every time you
tolerate that person--

00:30:05.780 --> 00:30:08.540
and you talk about your
values and behaviors.

00:30:08.540 --> 00:30:13.080
And you've got some jerk who's
kissing up and kicking down

00:30:13.080 --> 00:30:17.260
while getting good numbers,
you keep tolerating him.

00:30:17.260 --> 00:30:20.860
And you give speeches on
values, and mission, and beauty,

00:30:20.860 --> 00:30:24.090
and peace, and everything else.

00:30:24.090 --> 00:30:27.240
But you've got this person.

00:30:27.240 --> 00:30:29.890
Every promotion of
that person, every time

00:30:29.890 --> 00:30:34.980
that person gets promoted, you
ruin 50 speeches, 500 speeches.

00:30:34.980 --> 00:30:37.130
Stop flapping your lips.

00:30:37.130 --> 00:30:38.740
Don't talk about it.

00:30:38.740 --> 00:30:42.040
So that person with
high performing numbers

00:30:42.040 --> 00:30:46.540
and lousy values is
a killer of culture.

00:30:46.540 --> 00:30:49.429
It's a killer of culture.

00:30:49.429 --> 00:30:50.970
LASZLO BOCK: You
talk about, I think,

00:30:50.970 --> 00:30:52.094
this is a category of that.

