are watching and listening.

00:32:09.392 --> 00:32:11.600
So somebody who has great
numbers, great salespeople,

00:32:11.600 --> 00:32:15.470
brilliant engineer,
total jerk, horse's ass.

00:32:15.470 --> 00:32:16.860
You can see that.

00:32:16.860 --> 00:32:20.700
What about the people where
they're not at both extremes?

00:32:20.700 --> 00:32:24.390
Great numbers, but
they're a jerk sometimes.

00:32:24.390 --> 00:32:25.640
They kick down sometimes.

00:32:25.640 --> 00:32:26.890
They're kind of political.

00:32:26.890 --> 00:32:28.425
Where do you draw the line?

00:32:28.425 --> 00:32:29.300
Where would you call?

00:32:29.300 --> 00:32:31.300
How much of that kind of
behavior is acceptable?

00:32:31.300 --> 00:32:33.890
Is any of it, or is none of it?

00:32:33.890 --> 00:32:35.690
JACK WELCH: You can
tell-- do people

00:32:35.690 --> 00:32:37.590
want to hang out with them?

00:32:37.590 --> 00:32:39.900
Do they have a place
where people want to work?

00:32:39.900 --> 00:32:41.480
Are they attracting people?

00:32:41.480 --> 00:32:42.830
Or are people dodging them?

00:32:42.830 --> 00:32:45.600
LASZLO BOCK: Well, that's
one thing we've seen here.

00:32:45.600 --> 00:32:46.552
Because we do surveys.

00:32:46.552 --> 00:32:47.260
We love our data.

00:32:47.260 --> 00:32:49.530
We do surveys about what do
you think of your manager

00:32:49.530 --> 00:32:50.238
every six months?

00:32:50.238 --> 00:32:51.620
And one of things
that happens is

00:32:51.620 --> 00:32:54.600
we see people who are
kind of brutal, really

00:32:54.600 --> 00:32:55.760
rough, tough managers.

00:32:55.760 --> 00:32:58.120
And what ends up happening
is the teams end up

00:32:58.120 --> 00:32:59.677
giving them positive scores.

00:32:59.677 --> 00:33:01.260
Because they say,
well, you know what?

00:33:01.260 --> 00:33:02.300
I don't like working
for this person,

00:33:02.300 --> 00:33:03.772
but I know where I stand.

00:33:03.772 --> 00:33:04.480
Or you know what?

00:33:04.480 --> 00:33:06.060
I've learned more than
I've ever learned.

00:33:06.060 --> 00:33:07.010
Yeah, I get beat
up once in awhile,

00:33:07.010 --> 00:33:09.218
but I'm learning so much
because this person's direct

00:33:09.218 --> 00:33:10.171
and in my face.

00:33:10.171 --> 00:33:12.420
And what's interesting is
when those people move jobs,

00:33:12.420 --> 00:33:14.910
the leaders move jobs,
no one follows them.

00:33:14.910 --> 00:33:17.600
And the team kind of
goes-- [SIGH OF RELIEF]

00:33:17.600 --> 00:33:20.126
But every measurement
we have along the way,

00:33:20.126 --> 00:33:21.250
you look at it objectively.

00:33:21.250 --> 00:33:22.070
And people go like, oh yeah.

00:33:22.070 --> 00:33:22.903
You know, it's fine.

00:33:22.903 --> 00:33:24.117
I can deal with it.

00:33:24.117 --> 00:33:26.200
Is this like having a bad
boyfriend or girlfriend?

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:27.550
You just can't break up?

00:33:27.550 --> 00:33:29.510
What's the secret?

00:33:29.510 --> 00:33:31.334
JACK WELCH: No, you're
going to have some--

00:33:31.334 --> 00:33:33.250
LASZLO BOCK: And how do
you find those people?

00:33:33.250 --> 00:33:34.500
JACK WELCH: Look,
you're going to look

00:33:34.500 --> 00:33:36.605
till the last day you
breathe, and you're not

00:33:36.605 --> 00:33:39.150
going to get them all.

00:33:39.150 --> 00:33:41.200
You can get faked out
on this all the time.

00:33:41.200 --> 00:33:43.010
Nobody has a perfect system.

00:33:43.010 --> 00:33:45.280
The question is what's
a better system?

00:33:45.280 --> 00:33:46.720
It's always going to be that.

00:33:46.720 --> 00:33:50.810
Because you can always
argue against the perfect,

00:33:50.810 --> 00:33:53.390
but no system is perfect.

00:33:53.390 --> 00:33:55.950
But you've got to be
able to evaluate people

00:33:55.950 --> 00:33:58.630
on two axes, not one.

00:33:58.630 --> 00:34:00.810
And now you may
not get it right.

00:34:00.810 --> 00:34:03.870
You may not be
perfect, but you'll

00:34:03.870 --> 00:34:05.620
be better than any
other system out there.

00:34:05.620 --> 00:34:07.953
LASZLO BOCK: I think you're
right about the second axis.

00:34:07.953 --> 00:34:09.080
I think we need that.

00:34:09.080 --> 00:34:11.013
We absolutely do.

00:34:11.013 --> 00:34:12.929
I have one question I
want to say for the end,

00:34:12.929 --> 00:34:14.280
but I want to open
it up for questions

00:34:14.280 --> 00:34:15.719
either that are
submitted online,

00:34:15.719 --> 00:34:17.513
or if anyone in the
