00:34:22.719 --> 00:34:24.135
so we can get a
recording of that?

00:34:26.329 --> 00:34:26.870
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:34:26.870 --> 00:34:29.480
Thanks again for
coming to Google.

00:34:29.480 --> 00:34:31.750
One of the challenges
that any large company has

00:34:31.750 --> 00:34:35.114
is remote office workers
in developing their talent.

00:34:35.114 --> 00:34:37.030
What are some the best
strategies you've seen?

00:34:37.030 --> 00:34:39.113
I know you developed talent
in your remote offices

00:34:39.113 --> 00:34:40.000
when you were at GE.

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:41.500
What are some of
the best strategies

00:34:41.500 --> 00:34:44.290
you've seen for owning your
own career as a remote office

00:34:44.290 --> 00:34:45.659
worker?

00:34:45.659 --> 00:34:48.230
JACK WELCH: Well, I'll try
a couple, and you try some.

00:34:48.230 --> 00:34:51.960
We have an online
school, all remote.

00:34:51.960 --> 00:34:54.440
And the biggest
challenge is how do you

00:34:54.440 --> 00:34:58.190
socialize that office to believe
they belong to the mothership?

00:34:58.190 --> 00:34:59.490
It's a huge deal.

00:34:59.490 --> 00:35:01.170
You've got to make
all kinds of efforts.

00:35:01.170 --> 00:35:06.210
What we do is we have pivot
points on the computer screen.

00:35:06.210 --> 00:35:09.530
We know how many
contacts the dean

00:35:09.530 --> 00:35:11.990
has with every faculty
member per week.

00:35:11.990 --> 00:35:15.160
We know how many
contacts every dean has,

00:35:15.160 --> 00:35:17.740
every faculty member
has with every student.

00:35:17.740 --> 00:35:20.400
An online school is the
toughest thing in the world.

00:35:20.400 --> 00:35:23.260
People are working all day, go
home and do the work at night.

00:35:23.260 --> 00:35:24.597
They got a sick kid.

00:35:24.597 --> 00:35:26.180
The worst thing can
happen and they'll

00:35:26.180 --> 00:35:28.110
have to stay up all
night and do a paper,

00:35:28.110 --> 00:35:31.360
turn it in, get back, nice job.

00:35:31.360 --> 00:35:32.300
Killer.

00:35:32.300 --> 00:35:33.870
So they've got to
have that strength.

00:35:33.870 --> 00:35:38.720
So we monitor totally
the socialization aspects

00:35:38.720 --> 00:35:43.970
of faculty with the student,
the dean with the faculty.

00:35:43.970 --> 00:35:45.190
We've got to bring them in.

00:35:45.190 --> 00:35:48.930
And we talk about
subcontractors-- same thing.

00:35:48.930 --> 00:35:51.960
Subcontractor has seven clients.

00:35:51.960 --> 00:35:54.190
How do I make the
subcontractor like me

00:35:54.190 --> 00:35:57.220
more so I get his
heart and soul?

00:35:57.220 --> 00:35:58.720
Well, here, you feed him.

00:35:58.720 --> 00:36:00.800
You do all kinds
of things, but you

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:05.510
want to get that subcontractor
with more allegiance to you

00:36:05.510 --> 00:36:10.640
than to the other
six clients he has.

00:36:10.640 --> 00:36:12.710
So you're always working
on socialization.

00:36:12.710 --> 00:36:15.610
You're always bringing him into
the core as much as you can.

00:36:15.610 --> 00:36:17.800
You're measuring how
many contacts you have.

00:36:17.800 --> 00:36:21.220
You're doing all these
things to be sure that nobody

00:36:21.220 --> 00:36:23.830
feels they're out on an island.

00:36:23.830 --> 00:36:26.200
SUZY WELCH: I think
the main thing

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:30.770
is that if you don't actively
manage people who are working

00:36:30.770 --> 00:36:34.030
remotely or virtually, if
you don't actively manage it

00:36:34.030 --> 00:36:38.130
and you let it manage
itself, it falls apart.

00:36:38.130 --> 00:36:41.629
And so managers often can feel--
I felt that way myself when

00:36:41.629 --> 00:36:42.920
I was the editor of a magazine.

00:36:42.920 --> 00:36:45.179
I had a lot of people
not working in the office

00:36:45.179 --> 00:36:46.720
because editing can
be done anywhere.

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:48.616
And so a lot of people
were in life stages

00:36:48.616 --> 00:36:50.490
where they wanted and
needed to work at home.

00:36:50.490 --> 00:36:51.656
I worked with a lot of moms.

00:36:51.656 --> 00:36:54.250
And you want to
accommodate them,

00:36:54.250 --> 00:36:56.130
because they were so talented.

00:36:56.130 --> 00:37:00.090
And you're so busy with
what you're doing day to day

00:37:00.090 --> 00:37:01.270
that you just let it go.

00:37:01.270 --> 00:37:02.400
And then you realize
six months have gone by

00:37:02.400 --> 00:37:03.760
and you haven't
seen this person,

00:37:03.760 --> 00:37:05.150
and you haven't
really talked to them.

00:37:05.150 --> 00:37:07.608
Every interaction you've had
with them has been electronic.

00:37:07.608 --> 00:37:09.442
It was easy, and it was
working pretty well.

00:37:09.442 --> 00:37:11.982
And then you get that person
in, and you have a conversation.

00:37:11.982 --> 00:37:13.980
And you think how much
better it could've been.

00:37:13.980 --> 00:37:17.790
So I think you just have to
have it on your to-do list

00:37:17.790 --> 00:37:20.130
to actively manage
remote relationships.

00:37:20.130 --> 00:37:22.020
And if you just
let them go, which

00:37:22.020 --> 00:37:24.020
is the natural
human thing to do,

00:37:24.020 --> 00:37:26.940
you just are not getting
everything you can out of it,

00:37:26.940 --> 00:37:28.730
and teamwork suffers.

00:37:28.730 --> 00:37:31.130
JACK WELCH: The one
thing that Google

00:37:31.130 --> 00:37:33.780
could bring to the
world, if you will,

00:37:33.780 --> 00:37:38.420
is the ability to
socialize online education.

00:37:38.420 --> 00:37:40.920
No matter how hard we try,
whether it be Blackboard,

00:37:40.920 --> 00:37:43.220
whether it be this system
or the other system,

00:37:43.220 --> 00:37:47.570
we still are missing
the socialization link

00:37:47.570 --> 00:37:49.300
in our MBA program.

00:37:49.300 --> 00:37:51.420
That's the weak
link in the system.

00:37:51.420 --> 00:37:55.550
How do we get our students
more engaged in our game?

00:37:55.550 --> 00:37:57.800
SUZY WELCH: And new technology
comes out all the time.

00:37:57.800 --> 00:37:58.650
Believe me, we've seen it.

00:37:58.650 --> 00:37:59.800
JACK WELCH: It's not enough.

00:37:59.800 --> 00:38:00.780
SUZY WELCH: There's
nothing there yet.

00:38:00.780 --> 00:38:01.290
JACK WELCH: We
need breakthroughs.

00:38:01.290 --> 00:38:01.680
SUZY WELCH: Please do it!

00:38:01.680 --> 00:38:03.190
JACK WELCH: Please do it!

00:38:03.190 --> 00:38:05.030
And it would apply
to these offices.

00:38:05.030 --> 00:38:07.406
LASZLO BOCK: Are you Google
for Education customers?

00:38:07.406 --> 00:38:09.080
Because we can introduce
you to someone.

00:38:09.080 --> 00:38:11.190
JACK WELCH: We looked at
Noodle and stuff like that.

00:38:11.190 --> 00:38:11.981
We've looked at it.

00:38:11.981 --> 00:38:14.260
It isn't good enough.

00:38:14.260 --> 00:38:15.526
SUZY WELCH: Oh, oh.

00:38:15.526 --> 00:38:17.050
JACK WELCH: It isn't!

00:38:17.050 --> 00:38:20.393
No, it's a nice product,
but it isn't good enough.

00:38:20.393 --> 00:38:21.476
SUZY WELCH: Next frontier.

00:38:21.476 --> 00:38:22.322
LASZLO BOCK: OK.

00:38:22.322 --> 00:38:22.905
Next question?

00:38:25.767 --> 00:38:26.600
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:26.600 --> 00:38:30.170
So I had a question on
your career management.

00:38:30.170 --> 00:38:31.630
So there are two
approaches, right?

00:38:31.630 --> 00:38:34.190
One is you stay
within a company,

00:38:34.190 --> 00:38:38.010
and you grow, stay 20, 25
years within GE, or a company

00:38:38.010 --> 00:38:38.840
like that.

00:38:38.840 --> 00:38:42.410
And in the Silicon Valley,
it's more like every few years

00:38:42.410 --> 00:38:46.750
you get a promotion, as in
joining another company,

00:38:46.750 --> 00:38:48.920
and move around every few years.

00:38:48.920 --> 00:38:51.810
So how would you contrast
the two approaches

00:38:51.810 --> 00:38:54.049
to managing your career?

00:38:54.049 --> 00:38:56.090
JACK WELCH: I don't think
you manage your career.

00:38:56.090 --> 00:38:57.790
I think you manage your job.

00:38:57.790 --> 00:39:00.770
And what you do is you
overdeliver all the time,

00:39:00.770 --> 00:39:03.940
so you become a
commodity with gold stars

00:39:03.940 --> 00:39:05.820
everywhere so
everybody wants you.

00:39:05.820 --> 00:39:08.210
Anybody who's
managing their career,

00:39:08.210 --> 00:39:11.480
picking, I'll go here next,
and I'll go here next.

00:39:11.480 --> 00:39:14.620
And if I get that job,
then I'll get that job.

00:39:14.620 --> 00:39:15.660
Killer performer.

00:39:15.660 --> 00:39:17.360
Keep your eye on your job.

00:39:17.360 --> 00:39:19.860
Do better than anybody's
ever done on that job,

00:39:19.860 --> 00:39:21.360
and good things
will happen to you

00:39:21.360 --> 00:39:23.510
is my view of all those
things, whether you

00:39:23.510 --> 00:39:25.824
stay in that company or
go to another company.

00:39:25.824 --> 00:39:27.990
LASZLO BOCK: That's actually
in your career chapter.

00:39:27.990 --> 00:39:29.198
That's your first main point.

00:39:29.198 --> 00:39:30.670
You say don't
deliver, overdeliver.

00:39:30.670 --> 00:39:31.894
JACK WELCH: Yeah.

00:39:31.894 --> 00:39:34.060
LASZLO BOCK: And again,
that's something most people

00:39:34.060 --> 00:39:35.180
actually-- we do our best.

00:39:35.180 --> 00:39:36.638
But most of us
don't think about it

00:39:36.638 --> 00:39:38.970
as I'm going to kick
butt every single day.

00:39:38.970 --> 00:39:41.020
I'm going to exceed
everyone's expectations.

00:39:41.020 --> 00:39:42.830
SUZY WELCH: I think it's hard
to talk about that in this room.

00:39:42.830 --> 00:39:44.704
Because I'm going to
presume that most of you

00:39:44.704 --> 00:39:48.137
have been overdelivering since
you were in kindergarten.

00:39:48.137 --> 00:39:49.220
LASZLO BOCK: Most of them.

00:39:49.220 --> 00:39:50.270
Most of them.

00:39:50.270 --> 00:39:51.110
SUZY WELCH: OK,
but overdelivering

00:39:51.110 --> 00:39:52.193
is an interesting concept.

00:39:54.830 --> 00:39:57.040
For some people, it's
very natural, OK?

00:39:57.040 --> 00:39:58.570
But for others, it's not.

00:39:58.570 --> 00:40:02.040
By overdelivering it
means doing-- in school,

00:40:02.040 --> 00:40:03.230
you're taught to deliver.

00:40:03.230 --> 00:40:05.866
Even when you're at a fine
school, you get the assignment.

00:40:05.866 --> 00:40:06.990
You hand in the assignment.

00:40:06.990 --> 00:40:07.980
You do the assignment very well.

00:40:07.980 --> 00:40:09.600
And you're going to
get a great grade.

00:40:09.600 --> 00:40:12.141
But when you get into the real
world, it's a different thing.

00:40:12.141 --> 00:40:14.380
It's about making the
assignment much bigger.

00:40:14.380 --> 00:40:17.300
You're asked to do
X. And you actually

00:40:17.300 --> 00:40:20.350
give serious thought
to what more, what

00:40:20.350 --> 00:40:21.790
would be the bigger question.

00:40:21.790 --> 00:40:24.040
And so you deliver on X
and the bigger question.

00:40:26.710 --> 00:40:28.670
Jack tells a great
story about when he was

00:40:28.670 --> 00:40:29.950
trying to get out of the pile.

00:40:29.950 --> 00:40:31.800
Early on he was a
chemical engineer PhD.

00:40:31.800 --> 00:40:34.250
And his boss asked
him to present

00:40:34.250 --> 00:40:36.620
to his boss about some plastic.

00:40:36.620 --> 00:40:40.140
And instead, he presented to the
boss about the entire picture

00:40:40.140 --> 00:40:42.310
of the plastics industry
in 5 and 10 years,

00:40:42.310 --> 00:40:44.960
and did this McKinsey-like
presentation.

00:40:44.960 --> 00:40:46.070
They couldn't believe it.

00:40:46.070 --> 00:40:48.730
But that's overdelivering.

00:40:48.730 --> 00:40:52.365
And so the question is, are
you thinking expansively

00:40:52.365 --> 00:40:54.389
enough about your work?

00:40:54.389 --> 00:40:56.180
And that is the way to
manage your careers,

00:40:56.180 --> 00:40:57.750
if you are constantly
overdelivering.

00:40:57.750 --> 00:40:59.870
And you've got to have
a certain natural love

00:40:59.870 --> 00:41:01.550
and joy above the
work to be doing that,

00:41:01.550 --> 00:41:05.420
and a certain natural engagement
and curiosity about the work

00:41:05.420 --> 00:41:06.390
to be doing it.

00:41:06.390 --> 00:41:07.847
Otherwise, it's
really hard labor.

00:41:07.847 --> 00:41:09.430
JACK WELCH: One thing
to think about--

00:41:09.430 --> 00:41:13.010
and this is a simple little tip.

00:41:13.010 --> 00:41:17.700
Is your boss a lot smarter after
the meeting you had with him

00:41:17.700 --> 00:41:22.280
or her than before the
meeting took place?

00:41:22.280 --> 00:41:26.150
Is your boss going out and
can go to a cocktail party

00:41:26.150 --> 00:41:28.810
and can blow smoke
about something

00:41:28.810 --> 00:41:32.430
you gave him beautiful
insights into, or gave

00:41:32.430 --> 00:41:34.630
her insights into?

00:41:34.630 --> 00:41:36.710
Can he just end up smarter?

00:41:36.710 --> 00:41:42.640
Did the boss just sit through
a mind-numbing, boring regime

00:41:42.640 --> 00:41:46.200
of you telling him what you've
done, and how you're doing?

00:41:46.200 --> 00:41:50.670
Or have you given him
an expansive, broad view

00:41:50.670 --> 00:41:52.810
of the subject
that he asked about

00:41:52.810 --> 00:41:54.980
or the meeting was
supposed to be about?

00:41:54.980 --> 00:41:56.550
Think about that every time.

00:41:56.550 --> 00:41:59.760
Never go to a meeting
without making

00:41:59.760 --> 00:42:03.350
the boss you're dealing
with smarter for having sat

00:42:03.350 --> 00:42:05.090
through that meeting with you.

00:42:05.090 --> 00:42:06.595
Simple tip, but think about it.

00:42:06.595 --> 00:42:08.470
LASZLO BOCK: But what
I love-- and then we'll

00:42:08.470 --> 00:42:10.680
go to the question--
is that you keep

00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:14.405
coming back to things that
I, as an individual, control.

00:42:14.405 --> 00:42:16.030
I control how much
work I'm putting in.

00:42:16.030 --> 00:42:17.660
I control whether I'm
going above and beyond.

00:42:17.660 --> 00:42:19.868
I control what happens in
that meeting with the boss.

00:42:19.868 --> 00:42:23.250
I control do I ask about--
the woman who asks,

00:42:23.250 --> 00:42:24.230
what's my rating?

00:42:24.230 --> 00:42:26.430
What's going on?

00:42:26.430 --> 00:42:27.930
There's a huge focus on that.

00:42:27.930 --> 00:42:30.570
And that's very different
from the typical advice, which

00:42:30.570 --> 00:42:33.350
is, well, chart your course,
and check these boxes,

00:42:33.350 --> 00:42:34.414
and get this experience.

00:42:34.414 --> 00:42:35.330
JACK WELCH: I hate it.

00:42:35.330 --> 00:42:36.870
Why would you?

00:42:36.870 --> 00:42:38.610
We have an example in the book.

00:42:38.610 --> 00:42:41.530
Everyone says, oh, get a lot
of multifunctional experience.

00:42:41.530 --> 00:42:42.860
That'll do a lot for you.

00:42:42.860 --> 00:42:46.020
I always say, don't bring
skates to the basketball court.

00:42:46.020 --> 00:42:48.700
That's for hockey.

00:42:48.700 --> 00:42:50.970
Don't try skating on
the basketball court.

00:42:50.970 --> 00:42:53.510
Michael Jordan tried
playing baseball.

00:42:53.510 --> 00:42:55.470
He stunk at it.

00:42:55.470 --> 00:42:56.580
OK?

00:42:56.580 --> 00:42:58.580
He went into pro baseball.

00:42:58.580 --> 00:43:03.040
And do what you're good at and
just excel like hell at it,

00:43:03.040 --> 00:43:05.141
and the sky's the limit.

00:43:05.141 --> 00:43:07.140
LASZLO BOCK: That's how
a chemist becomes a CEO?

00:43:07.140 --> 00:43:07.926
JACK WELCH: Yeah.

00:43:07.926 --> 00:43:09.670
LASZLO BOCK: Yeah.

00:43:09.670 --> 00:43:10.917
How good a chemist were you?

00:43:10.917 --> 00:43:12.250
SUZY WELCH: A very good chemist.

00:43:12.250 --> 00:43:14.165
JACK WELCH: Pretty average
bear, chemical engineer.

00:43:14.165 --> 00:43:14.810
LASZLO BOCK: Yeah.

00:43:14.810 --> 00:43:16.143
JACK WELCH: Pretty average bear.

00:43:16.143 --> 00:43:17.200
LASZLO BOCK: Really?

00:43:17.200 --> 00:43:18.880
JACK WELCH: Compared
to other PhDs.

00:43:18.880 --> 00:43:21.680
But let me tell
you the difference.

00:43:21.680 --> 00:43:24.920
I got a PhD with a
Nobel Prize winner.

00:43:24.920 --> 00:43:26.990
I got out in three years.

00:43:26.990 --> 00:43:28.800
Most of my peers took seven.

00:43:28.800 --> 00:43:31.050
They were all
smarter than I was.

00:43:31.050 --> 00:43:32.500
But they doddled.

00:43:32.500 --> 00:43:33.780
They played in the lab.

00:43:33.780 --> 00:43:35.710
They liked lab hours.

00:43:35.710 --> 00:43:38.074
I wanted to get the
hell out of there.

00:43:38.074 --> 00:43:39.740
SUZY WELCH: He wanted
to be with people.

00:43:39.740 --> 00:43:41.365
JACK WELCH: I wanted
to be with people.

00:43:41.365 --> 00:43:43.380
LASZLO BOCK: Yeah.

00:43:43.380 --> 00:43:48.610
JACK WELCH: So I wasn't smarter
by any means, not even close.

00:43:48.610 --> 00:43:51.230
But I was in a hurry.

00:43:51.230 --> 00:43:52.730
LASZLO BOCK: I think
that might have

00:43:52.730 --> 00:43:54.870
made-- I think we could
debate the smarter part.

00:43:54.870 --> 00:43:56.344
I think you probably
did all right.

00:43:56.344 --> 00:43:57.510
JACK WELCH: I did all right.

00:43:57.510 --> 00:43:58.376
LASZLO BOCK: We'll see.

00:43:58.376 --> 00:44:00.140
We'll see, I guess,
in the next few years

00:44:00.140 --> 00:44:03.940
how things work out
for you, Jack Welch.

00:44:03.940 --> 00:44:05.020
Another question.

00:44:05.020 --> 00:44:06.320
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:44:06.320 --> 00:44:08.060
I was wondering if I could
ask a question about smaller

00:44:08.060 --> 00:44:08.580
companies.

00:44:08.580 --> 00:44:10.204
Because I think we
have a lot in common

00:44:10.204 --> 00:44:12.850
here with small companies.

00:44:12.850 --> 00:44:15.390
I was just curious if you,
having your experience at GE,

00:44:15.390 --> 00:44:18.055
a big corporation, if there
are any-- because I think

00:44:18.055 --> 00:44:20.680
small companies are often proud
of the fact that they're small,

00:44:20.680 --> 00:44:22.888
and they don't have much in
common with corporations.

00:44:22.888 --> 00:44:25.810
What do you think smaller
companies could incorporate--

00:44:25.810 --> 00:44:27.540
practices, learnings--
from a big company

00:44:27.540 --> 00:44:28.956
that you think
they often overlook

00:44:28.956 --> 00:44:31.400
or avoid intentionally?

00:44:31.400 --> 00:44:34.710
JACK WELCH: Well,
what a company always

00:44:34.710 --> 00:44:38.900
wants to be-- don't forget that
plastic story we started with.

00:44:38.900 --> 00:44:42.890
I was the first employee,
and 18 years later, we're

00:44:42.890 --> 00:44:45.610
a $16 billion company.

00:44:45.610 --> 00:44:46.750
We had one technician.

00:44:46.750 --> 00:44:49.635
I hired the first one, the
second one, the third one.

00:44:49.635 --> 00:44:52.320
Now, we had the luxury of
building that $16 billion

00:44:52.320 --> 00:44:56.040
company in a big corporation
that didn't know anything

00:44:56.040 --> 00:44:57.580
about plastics.

00:44:57.580 --> 00:44:59.530
So we were shielded, and
we had lots of money.

00:44:59.530 --> 00:45:01.030
We had a bank behind us.

00:45:01.030 --> 00:45:03.530
So we weren't out starting
it up from the ground.

00:45:03.530 --> 00:45:07.360
But what does a small
company never want to be?

00:45:07.360 --> 00:45:09.342
It never wants to
be a bureaucracy.

00:45:09.342 --> 00:45:10.800
What does a big
company want to be?

00:45:10.800 --> 00:45:12.530
It wants to get rid of layers.

00:45:12.530 --> 00:45:14.902
It wants to de-layer and
become a small company.

00:45:14.902 --> 00:45:16.610
But what does a small
company want to be?

00:45:16.610 --> 00:45:19.770
It wants to have leverage
in the marketplace.

00:45:19.770 --> 00:45:23.180
So it has to have unique
products to get leverage

00:45:23.180 --> 00:45:24.140
in the marketplace.

00:45:24.140 --> 00:45:25.490
It must be unique.

00:45:25.490 --> 00:45:28.100
It can't have just coverage.

00:45:28.100 --> 00:45:31.350
So you want the muscle
of a big company

00:45:31.350 --> 00:45:33.680
and the heart of
a small company.

00:45:33.680 --> 00:45:36.520
And all these things
don't go together.

00:45:36.520 --> 00:45:41.100
For example, when you talk
about business as a sport,

00:45:41.100 --> 00:45:44.480
the team with the
best players wins.

00:45:44.480 --> 00:45:46.130
That's what I happens in sports.

00:45:46.130 --> 00:45:49.100
The team with the best
players playing together wins.

00:45:49.100 --> 00:45:51.070
That's what happens in business.

00:45:51.070 --> 00:45:52.530
So it doesn't matter
whether you're

00:45:52.530 --> 00:45:54.770
a small business
or a big business,

00:45:54.770 --> 00:45:55.970
you want the best players.

00:45:55.970 --> 00:45:58.280
You want to constantly
reward the best.

00:45:58.280 --> 00:46:00.960
You want to do all the same
things, but you don't want--

00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:04.710
I was talking at LinkedIn
yesterday and talking here

00:46:04.710 --> 00:46:05.410
today.

00:46:05.410 --> 00:46:07.007
You guys are now a bureaucracy.

00:46:07.007 --> 00:46:09.340
You can have all the food and
all the stuff around here,

00:46:09.340 --> 00:46:10.610
but you're a bureaucracy.

00:46:10.610 --> 00:46:11.720
Come on.

00:46:11.720 --> 00:46:15.690
You got guys like him with
forms and all that stuff.

00:46:15.690 --> 00:46:16.190
It happens.

00:46:16.190 --> 00:46:16.690
It happens.

00:46:16.690 --> 00:46:18.898
LASZLO BOCK: I'm going to
survey them about this talk

00:46:18.898 --> 00:46:19.920
afterwards.

00:46:19.920 --> 00:46:21.070
I want the forms.

00:46:22.452 --> 00:46:24.160
SUZY WELCH: You have
to fear and loathe--

00:46:24.160 --> 00:46:25.743
JACK WELCH: You're
fighting every day,

00:46:25.743 --> 00:46:27.670
but you've got layers.

00:46:27.670 --> 00:46:29.340
You're adding layers.

00:46:29.340 --> 00:46:32.120
You can't have this many
people and not have layers.

00:46:32.120 --> 00:46:33.370
But you've got to fight.

00:46:33.370 --> 00:46:35.910
Every layer has to go through
the scrutiny of-- you've

00:46:35.910 --> 00:46:37.610
got to start from
the standpoint of I

00:46:37.610 --> 00:46:39.490
never want to have a layer.

00:46:39.490 --> 00:46:44.325
When you're starting a small
company, give them a salary.

00:46:44.325 --> 00:46:47.170
You don't have to
give them a title.

00:46:47.170 --> 00:46:48.000
Give them a salary.

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:50.040
Give them more span.

00:46:50.040 --> 00:46:52.740
I had 29 direct reports.

00:46:52.740 --> 00:46:55.300
Ideally, I should
have had 60 probably.

00:46:55.300 --> 00:46:57.580
Because if you don't have
a lot of draft reports,

00:46:57.580 --> 00:46:59.262
you can't meddle.

00:46:59.262 --> 00:47:00.720
And if you're good
people, you want

00:47:00.720 --> 00:47:02.916
them to have their own heads.

00:47:02.916 --> 00:47:04.790
So you've got to fight
like hell all the time

00:47:04.790 --> 00:47:06.820
not to layer up a place.

00:47:06.820 --> 00:47:08.110
Every layer is evil.

00:47:08.110 --> 00:47:10.430
It spins messages.

00:47:10.430 --> 00:47:12.020
It delays decision making.

00:47:12.020 --> 00:47:15.681
It does all these
terrible things.

00:47:15.681 --> 00:47:17.680
LASZLO BOCK: So on this
point, one of things you

00:47:17.680 --> 00:47:18.560
talk about, one of these--

00:47:18.560 --> 00:47:20.685
JACK WELCH: I probably
didn't answer your question,

00:47:20.685 --> 00:47:22.530
but you understand the theory.

00:47:22.530 --> 00:47:23.240
LASZLO BOCK: One
of the things you

00:47:23.240 --> 00:47:24.656
talk about in terms
of bureaucracy

00:47:24.656 --> 00:47:27.210
is you touch very
briefly on budgets.

00:47:27.210 --> 00:47:29.510
And you talk about how every
company has these budget

00:47:29.510 --> 00:47:32.170
negotiations internally about
how much you're going to spend.

00:47:32.170 --> 00:47:34.724
And you write-- there's
this beautiful line about,

00:47:34.724 --> 00:47:36.890
and somehow, you always end
up in the middle, right?

00:47:36.890 --> 00:47:40.832
Because people-- how do
you cut through that?

00:47:40.832 --> 00:47:42.290
How do you get
people to be honest?

00:47:42.290 --> 00:47:45.970
JACK WELCH: Look, the
main point in this book

00:47:45.970 --> 00:47:48.090
is what a leader's job is.

00:47:48.090 --> 00:47:51.940
It's to create an atmosphere
of truth and trust,

00:47:51.940 --> 00:47:54.510
where every meeting-- you can
have a neon light up here--

00:47:54.510 --> 00:47:56.690
there's only truth
being spun here.

00:47:56.690 --> 00:48:00.590
No spin, no BS.

00:48:00.590 --> 00:48:02.180
We want the truth only.

00:48:02.180 --> 00:48:03.950
Because everybody
comes in with a pitch,

00:48:03.950 --> 00:48:05.790
and they have their own biases.

00:48:05.790 --> 00:48:07.400
They're pitching
it, spinning it.

00:48:07.400 --> 00:48:10.910
Let's take the bunch of
review as a perfect example.

00:48:10.910 --> 00:48:12.090
I'm in the field.

00:48:12.090 --> 00:48:16.350
I come in to headquarters at
Google here with my budget.

00:48:16.350 --> 00:48:19.470
And I'll come in and
say the market stinks.

00:48:19.470 --> 00:48:23.240
The world's coming to an end.

00:48:23.240 --> 00:48:24.670
The Chinese are killing us.

00:48:24.670 --> 00:48:27.050
This is happening here.

00:48:27.050 --> 00:48:29.780
All I can do is two.

00:48:29.780 --> 00:48:34.910
And then the bosses here
will say, I need four.

00:48:34.910 --> 00:48:37.670
And you go into
a windowless room

00:48:37.670 --> 00:48:39.200
and sit there and bang heads.

00:48:39.200 --> 00:48:43.700
There'll be no customers,
no analysts, nobody around.

00:48:43.700 --> 00:48:46.230
And you'll sit there for seven
hours with presentations,

00:48:46.230 --> 00:48:48.390
and slides, and all that stuff.

00:48:48.390 --> 00:48:51.300
And you'll come out with three.

00:48:51.300 --> 00:48:53.760
That's the budget for the year.

00:48:53.760 --> 00:48:55.440
Nothing will have happened.

00:48:55.440 --> 00:48:57.170
The only measurements
that count is

00:48:57.170 --> 00:49:00.050
how did you do
against last year,

00:49:00.050 --> 00:49:02.270
and how did you do against
any competitors you

00:49:02.270 --> 00:49:03.410
measure against?

00:49:03.410 --> 00:49:04.722
That's all that counts.

00:49:04.722 --> 00:49:06.680
Measuring against a budget
is the dumbest thing

00:49:06.680 --> 00:49:10.860
that was ever invented in
business-- the dumbest thing.

00:49:10.860 --> 00:49:12.560
Because a budget
is a negotiation

00:49:12.560 --> 00:49:14.530
between two human beings.

00:49:14.530 --> 00:49:16.340
It has nothing to
do with the world.

00:49:16.340 --> 00:49:17.520
It's crazy.

00:49:17.520 --> 00:49:18.020
It's stupid.

00:49:18.020 --> 00:49:20.395
LASZLO BOCK: Yeah, you about
looking at variance instead,

00:49:20.395 --> 00:49:22.450
right?

00:49:22.450 --> 00:49:24.210
You talk about variance instead?

00:49:24.210 --> 00:49:27.110
JACK WELCH: Everything's
variance in my mind.

00:49:27.110 --> 00:49:31.690
We have a chapter in here--
"Don't be Afraid of Finance."

00:49:31.690 --> 00:49:34.730
If you understand
variance analysis,

00:49:34.730 --> 00:49:37.600
how does the marketing
budget compare to last year?

00:49:37.600 --> 00:49:39.290
And are the sales
going up because you

00:49:39.290 --> 00:49:42.240
doubled the marketing
budget, or are they not?

00:49:42.240 --> 00:49:44.720
Everything against a
variance, against last year,

00:49:44.720 --> 00:49:47.220
against two years ago.

00:49:47.220 --> 00:49:49.530
And you're acquiring
a company, why

00:49:49.530 --> 00:49:52.900
are you going to spend that much
versus what they spent before?

00:49:52.900 --> 00:49:53.854
Everything's variance.

00:49:53.854 --> 00:49:54.520
It's arithmetic.

00:49:54.520 --> 00:50:00.160
Is not DCRRs, or DSDCFs,
or IRRs, and all that crap.

00:50:00.160 --> 00:50:02.010
You don't need it.

00:50:02.010 --> 00:50:03.630
You need to understand variance.

00:50:03.630 --> 00:50:06.132
That's what you need in finance.

00:50:06.132 --> 00:50:08.090
LASZLO BOCK: I don't know
if Cliff's still here

00:50:08.090 --> 00:50:11.047
who has the Dory questions,
but if there's one--

00:50:11.047 --> 00:50:12.130
AUDIENCE: We got them all.

00:50:12.130 --> 00:50:12.460
LASZLO BOCK: Oh,
we got them all?

00:50:12.460 --> 00:50:13.572
OK.

00:50:13.572 --> 00:50:15.030
And if there's any
other questions,

00:50:15.030 --> 00:50:16.830
we've got a few minutes left.

00:50:16.830 --> 00:50:21.670
Two last things, one
super-- well, actually,

