00:52:18.710 --> 00:52:20.895
But I think what it
is, and you've seen it,

00:52:20.895 --> 00:52:22.580
and you've all experienced it.

00:52:22.580 --> 00:52:25.620
It's this preponderance, this
desire, this burning desire

00:52:25.620 --> 00:52:29.670
in an individual to see
the people working for him

00:52:29.670 --> 00:52:31.410
or her growing.

00:52:31.410 --> 00:52:34.160
And they get really psyched
about giving promotions,

00:52:34.160 --> 00:52:37.420
and raises, and seeing
people get things right,

00:52:37.420 --> 00:52:41.560
and just getting better.

00:52:41.560 --> 00:52:44.020
We've all worked for bosses
with the generosity gene who

00:52:44.020 --> 00:52:48.990
have this incredible
heart of love, really,

00:52:48.990 --> 00:52:53.310
for people to grow, and to get
better, and really love you

00:52:53.310 --> 00:52:55.515
as an individual, and
see you get more money,

00:52:55.515 --> 00:52:57.890
and see you get promoted, and
see you even leave the team

00:52:57.890 --> 00:52:59.650
to go on to bigger
and better things.

00:52:59.650 --> 00:53:02.290
And then we've all had the
bosses who steal your idea

00:53:02.290 --> 00:53:06.010
and use it as their
own, and really

00:53:06.010 --> 00:53:08.390
get stingy around
raises, and really get

00:53:08.390 --> 00:53:10.910
stingy about celebrating you.

00:53:10.910 --> 00:53:12.650
And so if you're
looking for what team

00:53:12.650 --> 00:53:15.770
you're going to go to-- because
you'll go the extra mile.

00:53:15.770 --> 00:53:17.860
And the team will be
that much more energized

00:53:17.860 --> 00:53:21.850
when the leader has got
this generosity gene.

00:53:21.850 --> 00:53:24.350
JACK WELCH: And if you think
about it-- stay there a minute.

00:53:24.350 --> 00:53:26.490
If you think about
it, if you think

00:53:26.490 --> 00:53:29.430
about it in this
room, all of you,

00:53:29.430 --> 00:53:31.760
you've worked for both types.

00:53:31.760 --> 00:53:34.300
You've worked for people
with a generous spirit.

00:53:34.300 --> 00:53:37.010
You've worked for people
that didn't have it.

00:53:37.010 --> 00:53:38.530
Where was it more fun?

00:53:38.530 --> 00:53:41.400
Where was it more enjoyable?

00:53:41.400 --> 00:53:43.920
Because when I look
at the people that

00:53:43.920 --> 00:53:47.290
have led in our company, in
the companies I've worked with,

00:53:47.290 --> 00:53:50.300
74 private equity
companies and GE.

00:53:50.300 --> 00:53:55.230
If I look at these guys, the
winning people, male or female,

00:53:55.230 --> 00:53:57.190
they had this experience.

00:53:57.190 --> 00:54:00.400
They loved to see
their people grow.

00:54:00.400 --> 00:54:01.850
The biggest thrill
for me is we've

00:54:01.850 --> 00:54:03.940
got-- you can count
them-- 50, 60,

00:54:03.940 --> 00:54:07.730
70 CEOs out there
now who work for me.

00:54:07.730 --> 00:54:12.560
Many of them-- you refer to
one in your book, Dave Cote.

00:54:12.560 --> 00:54:16.100
They were all chief
executives of GE businesses.

00:54:16.100 --> 00:54:17.960
That's the biggest
turn-on in the world

00:54:17.960 --> 00:54:21.540
to have the Boeing CEO, the
Honeywell CEO, the Home Depot

00:54:21.540 --> 00:54:22.950
CEO.

00:54:22.950 --> 00:54:26.050
All these people
were my partners.

00:54:26.050 --> 00:54:27.340
They're my friends.

00:54:27.340 --> 00:54:29.720
And the nice thing--
Google's got to have that.

00:54:29.720 --> 00:54:31.630
They probably have a
lot of it now already,

00:54:31.630 --> 00:54:36.175
whether it be Marissa Meyer,
or whoever else is out there.

00:54:36.175 --> 00:54:37.890
You'll have the same
raft because you've

00:54:37.890 --> 00:54:40.990
got a human resource
process that works.

00:54:40.990 --> 00:54:42.920
And that's one of the
great thrills of life

00:54:42.920 --> 00:54:47.750
to see these people sprouting up
all over the place from Google.

00:54:47.750 --> 00:54:51.760
And Google will be the
GE of the last 20 years,

00:54:51.760 --> 00:54:54.140
20 years ago, going forward.

00:54:54.140 --> 00:54:57.310
They'll have tons of CEOs
out there running companies.

00:54:57.310 --> 00:54:59.739
And it'll be the biggest
turn-on for Google.

00:54:59.739 --> 00:55:00.530
LASZLO BOCK: It is.

00:55:00.530 --> 00:55:01.029
It is.

00:55:01.029 --> 00:55:02.780
It's amazing to watch, folks.

00:55:02.780 --> 00:55:04.796
So last question
for each of you.

00:55:04.796 --> 00:55:07.310
JACK WELCH: Thanks
for that question.

00:55:07.310 --> 00:55:10.210
LASZLO BOCK: You write in one
of the concluding chapters.

00:55:10.210 --> 00:55:12.190
You say, to quote
from Mark Twain,

00:55:12.190 --> 00:55:14.380
"the two most important
days in your life

00:55:14.380 --> 00:55:18.600
are the day you were born and
the day you figure out why."

00:55:18.600 --> 00:55:20.740
I'd love, if you don't
mind, for you to share

00:55:20.740 --> 00:55:21.870
why were you each born?

00:55:21.870 --> 00:55:23.740
Why are you here?

00:55:32.384 --> 00:55:34.300
SUZY WELCH: I happen to
be a devout Christian.

00:55:34.300 --> 00:55:36.490
So for me the
answer is just going

00:55:36.490 --> 00:55:39.160
to be I was born to glorify God.

00:55:39.160 --> 00:55:41.505
So I think that's a
really personal thing,

00:55:41.505 --> 00:55:43.880
and probably if there's any
other Christians in the room,

00:55:43.880 --> 00:55:44.870
they would have the same answer.

00:55:44.870 --> 00:55:46.290
So that would be the answer.

00:55:46.290 --> 00:55:52.030
Now, how I glorify God is I
have a gift, which is writing.

00:55:52.030 --> 00:55:56.570
And I discovered that I had
that gift, like many writers do,

00:55:56.570 --> 00:55:58.010
when I was really young.

00:55:58.010 --> 00:56:01.340
I started a diary when
I was nine years old.

00:56:01.340 --> 00:56:02.950
And I wrote in it
every single day.

00:56:02.950 --> 00:56:05.530
And if I didn't write in
it, I felt like something

00:56:05.530 --> 00:56:06.290
was really wrong.

00:56:06.290 --> 00:56:08.415
So I was really lucky to
be able to have that gift.

00:56:08.415 --> 00:56:10.440
And then I've been
unbelievably blessed

00:56:10.440 --> 00:56:13.060
to find many different
ways to use that gift

00:56:13.060 --> 00:56:14.670
to change people's lives.

00:56:14.670 --> 00:56:17.000
And in fact, when
I was running HBR

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:18.960
when I would try
to recruit people,

00:56:18.960 --> 00:56:22.220
I would say please come join
me help change the world.

00:56:22.220 --> 00:56:23.430
That was just incredible.

00:56:23.430 --> 00:56:24.730
So I was able to use my gift.

00:56:24.730 --> 00:56:26.959
And all writers use their
gifts in different ways.

00:56:26.959 --> 00:56:28.084
LAZLO BOCK: That's amazing.

00:56:28.084 --> 00:56:30.100
Thank you.

00:56:30.100 --> 00:56:32.680
JACK WELCH: No, I just
happened to be lucky.

00:56:32.680 --> 00:56:38.350
Luck plays an enormous part in
where you get to in these jobs.

00:56:38.350 --> 00:56:39.155
You bust your butt.

00:56:39.155 --> 00:56:40.210
You do all these things.

00:56:40.210 --> 00:56:42.130
But I love people.

00:56:42.130 --> 00:56:45.920
And when I took this job
on, from the first plastic,

00:56:45.920 --> 00:56:48.430
I loved my first employee,
to my second employee,

00:56:48.430 --> 00:56:49.740
to my third employee.

00:56:49.740 --> 00:56:51.331
I like hanging out.

00:56:51.331 --> 00:56:55.020
And I like being with people.

00:56:55.020 --> 00:56:58.460
And contrary to
what Laszlo feels--

00:56:58.460 --> 00:57:00.790
and he's smarter and
brighter in some ways.

00:57:00.790 --> 00:57:02.305
SUZY WELCH: Going for you.

00:57:02.305 --> 00:57:04.910
JACK WELCH: No, I
believe in my gut.

00:57:04.910 --> 00:57:06.660
I'm a gut guy.

00:57:06.660 --> 00:57:07.930
I'm not an analyst.

00:57:07.930 --> 00:57:11.990
I have a PhD and all that stuff,
but I believe in gut, and feel,

00:57:11.990 --> 00:57:14.290
and touch, and people.

00:57:14.290 --> 00:57:18.120
And I'll hire, and I'll
make mistakes with my gut

00:57:18.120 --> 00:57:19.310
many times.

00:57:19.310 --> 00:57:20.740
But so far, people like me.

00:57:20.740 --> 00:57:21.790
They work hard for me.

00:57:21.790 --> 00:57:23.370
We all work as a team.

00:57:23.370 --> 00:57:24.670
It isn't me.

00:57:24.670 --> 00:57:27.560
But I always hire people
smarter than me in every job

00:57:27.560 --> 00:57:29.260
I've ever been in.

00:57:29.260 --> 00:57:30.190
And I like them.

00:57:30.190 --> 00:57:32.380
I like hang around with them.

00:57:32.380 --> 00:57:36.556
If you like people,
it's a fun job.

00:57:36.556 --> 00:57:37.940
It's a great job.

00:57:37.940 --> 00:57:41.330
And that's what I like,
and so it all worked out.

00:57:41.330 --> 00:57:43.660
I was captain of sports
all through college.

00:57:43.660 --> 00:57:46.330
I was captain of
sports in high school.

00:57:46.330 --> 00:57:50.160
People tend to
let me be captain.

00:57:50.160 --> 00:57:54.400
So it seemed to be fun, and
I've never stopped liking it.

00:57:54.400 --> 00:57:56.240
That's why we keep doing this.

00:57:56.240 --> 00:57:57.530
We love these interchanges.

00:57:57.530 --> 00:57:59.420
We learn everywhere we go.

00:57:59.420 --> 00:58:02.480
We see these magnificent
people doing things.

00:58:02.480 --> 00:58:04.480
And it's wonderful
to be out here where

00:58:04.480 --> 00:58:05.730
you're seeing all this growth.

00:58:05.730 --> 00:58:09.750
Because growth really
is an elixir of life.

00:58:09.750 --> 00:58:11.100
It truly is.

00:58:11.100 --> 00:58:14.906
It gives you a whole
new jolt. And we're

00:58:14.906 --> 00:58:16.280
lucky enough and
fortunate enough

00:58:16.280 --> 00:58:18.500
to have people come
and listen to us.

00:58:18.500 --> 00:58:19.906
So thanks for being here.

00:58:19.906 --> 00:58:20.822
LAZLO BOCK: Thank you.

00:58:20.822 --> 00:58:22.790
[APPLAUSE]

00:58:25.742 --> 00:58:29.680
And if I can just say two
quick things in closing.

00:58:29.680 --> 00:58:32.870
One is it's not often you have
a discussion about a business

00:58:32.870 --> 00:58:36.540
book that then hinges on
talk about God, and love,

00:58:36.540 --> 00:58:39.116
and changing the world,
and transformation.

00:58:39.116 --> 00:58:41.240
So it's an incredible gift
to have both of you here

00:58:41.240 --> 00:58:44.270
and to have you share the
wisdom you've both accumulated.

00:58:44.270 --> 00:58:45.710
So thank you on
behalf of Google.

00:58:45.710 --> 00:58:46.540
SUZY WELCH: Thank you.

00:58:46.540 --> 00:58:48.250
LAZLO BOCK: The other thing
is I know just for this room

00:58:48.250 --> 00:58:50.749
that you both offered to hang
around and say hello to folks,

00:58:50.749 --> 00:58:53.310
anybody wants to
come up and chat.

00:58:53.310 --> 00:58:54.810
And we have some
books back there

00:58:54.810 --> 00:58:56.560
that you're free to
take, some others when

00:58:56.560 --> 00:58:59.270
we run out that you're free
to purchase at a discount.

00:58:59.270 --> 00:59:02.034
I imagine your hands aren't
completely sore and broken?

00:59:02.034 --> 00:59:03.950
JACK WELCH: No, we're
happy to sign any books.

00:59:03.950 --> 00:59:05.630
LAZLO BOCK: You can probably
get a few signatures.

00:59:05.630 --> 00:59:07.310
But thank you, sincerely,
for sharing your message.

00:59:07.310 --> 00:59:07.690
SUZY WELCH: Hey, thank
you for being here.

00:59:07.690 --> 00:59:08.000
Thank you.

00:59:08.000 --> 00:59:08.350
JACK WELCH: Laszlo, thank you.

00:59:08.350 --> 00:59:09.250
LAZLO BOCK: Really
appreciate it.

00:59:09.250 --> 00:59:09.850
Real pleasure.

